00:01:03.220 --> 00:01:06.500
or to seek relationships on
the side, so-called infidelity.

00:01:06.500 --> 00:01:08.400
I'm certainly not going
to encourage or discourage

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:09.350
any of these behaviors.

00:01:09.350 --> 00:01:12.730
I'm simply going to cover the
peer-reviewed scientific data

00:01:12.730 --> 00:01:16.870
on all these aspects of
desire, love, and attachment.

00:01:16.870 --> 00:01:20.300
I'm going to discuss how our
childhood attachment styles,

00:01:20.300 --> 00:01:24.780
as they're called, influence
our adult attachment styles.

00:01:24.780 --> 00:01:26.010
Yes, you heard that right.

00:01:26.010 --> 00:01:30.700
How we attached or did not
attach to primary caregivers

00:01:30.700 --> 00:01:35.340
in our childhood has much
to do with how we attach

00:01:35.340 --> 00:01:39.080
or fail to attach to
romantic partners as adults,

00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:41.950
because the same neural circuits,

00:01:41.950 --> 00:01:44.440
the neurons and their
connections in the brain and body

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:47.770
that underlie attachment
between infant and caregiver,

00:01:47.770 --> 00:01:50.400
between toddler and
parent or other caregiver,

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:53.210
and during adolescence
and in our teenage years

00:01:53.210 --> 00:01:57.110
are repurposed for adult
romantic attachments.

00:01:57.110 --> 00:01:59.270
I know that might be a
little eerie to think about,

00:01:59.270 --> 00:02:01.030
but indeed that is true.

00:02:01.030 --> 00:02:04.180
Now the fortunate thing is that
regardless of our childhood

00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:07.840
attachment styles and
experiences, the neural circuits

00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:11.350
for desire, love and
attachment are quite plastic.

00:02:11.350 --> 00:02:14.270
They are amenable to
change in response to both

00:02:14.270 --> 00:02:18.600
what we think and what we
feel as well as what we do.

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:22.080
However, all three aspects
that we're discussing today,

00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:24.090
desire, love and attachment

00:02:24.090 --> 00:02:27.030
are also strongly biologically driven.

00:02:27.030 --> 00:02:29.550
We're going to talk about
biological mechanisms

00:02:29.550 --> 00:02:31.110
such as hormones,

00:02:31.110 --> 00:02:33.360
biological mechanisms
such as neurochemicals,

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:36.310
things like dopamine,
oxytocin and serotonin,

00:02:36.310 --> 00:02:39.910
and neural circuits, brain
areas, and indeed areas

00:02:39.910 --> 00:02:42.930
of the body that interact
with the brain that control

00:02:42.930 --> 00:02:45.180
whether or not we desire somebody or not,

00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:47.410
whether or not we lose
or increase our desire

00:02:47.410 --> 00:02:51.010
for somebody over time,
whether or not we fall in love,

00:02:51.010 --> 00:02:54.000
what love means, and whether
or not the relationships

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.800
we form continue to include the elements

00:02:56.800 --> 00:02:59.710
of desire and love over time or not.

00:02:59.710 --> 00:03:02.150
In order to illustrate just
how powerfully our biology

00:03:02.150 --> 00:03:04.090
can shape our perception
of the attractiveness

00:03:04.090 --> 00:03:06.490
of other people, I want to
share with you the results

00:03:06.490 --> 00:03:07.910
of a couple of studies.

00:03:07.910 --> 00:03:09.290
Both studies explore

00:03:09.290 --> 00:03:12.190
how people rate other
people's attractiveness.

00:03:12.190 --> 00:03:16.290
And in both studies, the
major variable is that women

00:03:16.290 --> 00:03:18.870
are at different stages
of their menstrual cycle.

00:03:18.870 --> 00:03:22.480
Now in the first study, men
are rating the attractiveness

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:25.410
of women according to
the smell of those women.

00:03:25.410 --> 00:03:26.810
Now they're not smelling them directly.

00:03:26.810 --> 00:03:29.870
They're smelling clothing
that women wore for a couple

00:03:29.870 --> 00:03:32.900
of days at different phases
of their menstrual cycle.

00:03:32.900 --> 00:03:36.310
And what they find is that men
will rate the odors of women

00:03:36.310 --> 00:03:39.400
as most attractive if those women wore

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:41.800
those shirts, that clothing,

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:44.810
in the pre-ovulatory phase
of their cycle, okay?

00:03:44.810 --> 00:03:48.540
So this is not to say that men
do not find women attractive

00:03:48.540 --> 00:03:49.801
at other stages of their cycle.

00:03:49.801 --> 00:03:53.470
It is to say that men find women's odors

00:03:53.470 --> 00:03:57.540
particularly attractive, if
those odors were worn by women

00:03:57.540 --> 00:03:59.720
that are in the pre-ovulatory phase

00:03:59.720 --> 00:04:02.210
of their menstrual cycle, okay?

00:04:02.210 --> 00:04:05.850
Now, there was also a study
that was done where women

00:04:05.850 --> 00:04:07.099
at different stages of
their menstrual cycle

00:04:07.099 --> 00:04:09.970
are rating the odors of men.

00:04:09.970 --> 00:04:13.420
And a similar but mirror
symmetric result was found

00:04:13.420 --> 00:04:16.290
such that women who are
in the pre-ovulatory phase

00:04:16.290 --> 00:04:19.530
of their menstrual cycle
will rate men's odors

00:04:19.530 --> 00:04:23.450
as more attractive than at
other stages of their cycle.

00:04:23.450 --> 00:04:25.810
So the simple way to put
this is that there seems

00:04:25.810 --> 00:04:28.710
to be something special
about the pre-ovulatory phase

00:04:28.710 --> 00:04:31.520
of a woman's menstrual cycle
that makes men rate them

00:04:31.520 --> 00:04:35.260
as more attractive during
that time and women rate men

00:04:35.260 --> 00:04:38.510
as more attractive during
that particular time as well.

00:04:38.510 --> 00:04:41.410
So this is a bidirectional effect.

00:04:41.410 --> 00:04:43.660
The way that the second study was done,

00:04:43.660 --> 00:04:47.460
where women are rating men was
not just to smell the odors

00:04:47.460 --> 00:04:50.200
of those men on t-shirts, they did that,

00:04:50.200 --> 00:04:52.370
but they correlated
that with whether or not

00:04:52.370 --> 00:04:53.690
the shirts were worn by men

00:04:53.690 --> 00:04:56.660
that were particularly
physically symmetrical.

00:04:56.660 --> 00:04:58.670
They actually had these
men divided into groups.

00:04:58.670 --> 00:05:00.290
It was more of a continuum rather,

00:05:00.290 --> 00:05:03.550
rated according to body
symmetry and face symmetry.

00:05:03.550 --> 00:05:07.070
And women preferred more symmetrical men

00:05:07.070 --> 00:05:09.810
when they were doing the preference test

00:05:09.810 --> 00:05:12.440
during the pre-ovulatory
phase of their cycle.

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:13.828
So again, the point is
that that pre-ovulatory

00:05:13.828 --> 00:05:16.010
phase of the cycle seems to create

00:05:16.010 --> 00:05:19.410
a bidirectional mutual attractiveness.

00:05:19.410 --> 00:05:22.010
Now, also extremely
interesting is that this effect

00:05:22.010 --> 00:05:25.240
does really seem to have
something to do with ovulation.

00:05:25.240 --> 00:05:27.440
Because in both studies,

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:30.370
they had women that were taking
oral contraception or not.

00:05:30.370 --> 00:05:33.180
And what they found was
if a woman is taking

00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:36.550
oral contraception, it prevented
that peak and perceived

00:05:36.550 --> 00:05:41.430
attractiveness by the men,
meaning men no longer perceived

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:43.180
a woman to be more attractive

00:05:43.180 --> 00:05:45.310
at a particular phase of their cycle.

00:05:45.310 --> 00:05:49.380
And also women taking oral
contraception no longer preferred

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:51.730
the odors of more symmetrical men

00:05:51.730 --> 00:05:54.190
during the pre-ovulatory
phase of their cycle.

00:05:54.190 --> 00:05:57.170
Now, I want to make sure
that it's especially clear

00:05:57.170 --> 00:06:01.430
that it is not the case that
oral contraception reduced

00:06:01.430 --> 00:06:03.520
the perception of a woman as attractive,

00:06:03.520 --> 00:06:05.330
that did not happen in these studies.

00:06:05.330 --> 00:06:09.530
It reduced the further
increase in a male's perception

00:06:09.530 --> 00:06:10.580
of her as attractive.

00:06:10.580 --> 00:06:13.230
And if women took oral contraception,

00:06:13.230 --> 00:06:18.120
it prevented them from
preferring more symmetrical men

00:06:18.120 --> 00:06:20.150
based on the odors of those men.

00:06:20.150 --> 00:06:21.680
Now I realize there are
a lot of variables here.

00:06:21.680 --> 00:06:22.783
We've got odors, we've got symmetry,

00:06:22.783 --> 00:06:26.240
we've got menstrual cycle,
pre-ovulatory, non pre-ovulatory.

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:28.210
And we have whether or not people

00:06:28.210 --> 00:06:29.710
are taking contraception or not.

00:06:29.710 --> 00:06:32.680
But the basic finding is that
depending on where women are

00:06:32.680 --> 00:06:35.810
in their menstrual cycle,
influences both men's perception

00:06:35.810 --> 00:06:39.450
of them as attractive and
their perception of men

00:06:39.450 --> 00:06:43.390
as attractive and oral contraception
eliminates that effect.

00:06:43.390 --> 00:06:46.350
So I share with you those
data to illustrate that

00:06:46.350 --> 00:06:50.500
we often think that somebody
is attractive or not based on,

00:06:50.500 --> 00:06:52.390
I don't know, how they look,

00:06:52.390 --> 00:06:54.530
their skin, their hair, et cetera,

00:06:54.530 --> 00:06:58.400
but it also illustrates that
their odor is a powerful cue

00:06:58.400 --> 00:06:59.810
for some people more than others.

00:06:59.810 --> 00:07:02.030
Some of us tend to be more
factory driven than others.

