00:14:13.210 --> 00:14:15.450
Let's talk about desire,
love, and attachment.

00:14:15.450 --> 00:14:17.081
And of course, these are topics

00:14:17.081 --> 00:14:18.790
that grab tremendous interest.

00:14:18.790 --> 00:14:21.800
So it's worth us defining
our terms a little bit

00:14:21.800 --> 00:14:23.860
before going any further.

00:14:23.860 --> 00:14:26.930
Of course, we can have many
different kinds of loves.

00:14:26.930 --> 00:14:29.990
There's romantic love,
there's love of family,

00:14:29.990 --> 00:14:32.640
so-called familial love,
there's love of pets.

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:34.270
We can even love objects,

00:14:34.270 --> 00:14:36.310
where we can feel as if we love objects.

00:14:36.310 --> 00:14:37.710
We can love certain activities.

00:14:37.710 --> 00:14:40.260
We can have friends that we
love and so on and so forth.

00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:41.830
The word love is used to encompass

00:14:41.830 --> 00:14:44.450
a lot of different types of relationships.

00:14:44.450 --> 00:14:47.900
Today, we are mainly going to
be focused on romantic love

00:14:47.900 --> 00:14:51.210
and the neural mechanisms
of romantic love.

00:14:51.210 --> 00:14:52.780
I want to acknowledge here at the outset

00:14:52.780 --> 00:14:55.130
that most of the studies of romantic love

00:14:55.130 --> 00:14:58.860
have focused on monogamous
heterosexual love.

00:14:58.860 --> 00:15:02.300
And also when we talk about
studies focused on desire,

00:15:02.300 --> 00:15:05.290
and attractiveness, and
attachment, that's also the case.

00:15:05.290 --> 00:15:08.270
And that simply reflects the
general bias of the literature

00:15:08.270 --> 00:15:10.660
over the last 50 to 100 years.

00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:13.210
It does, of course, not
rule out that similar

00:15:13.210 --> 00:15:15.430
or different mechanisms could be at play

00:15:15.430 --> 00:15:17.570
in non-monogamous relationships,

00:15:17.570 --> 00:15:19.600
in homosexual relationships,

00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:22.930
or in relationships of
any kind or variation.

00:15:22.930 --> 00:15:26.420
It's also worth us defining
our terms around desire.

00:15:26.420 --> 00:15:29.370
It can mean lust, it can mean the desire

00:15:29.370 --> 00:15:30.950
for long-term partnership.

00:15:30.950 --> 00:15:33.520
So we need to define our
terms and throughout I will do

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:37.350
my best to very carefully
define what I mean by desire,

00:15:37.350 --> 00:15:40.683
what I mean by love, and
what I mean by attachment.

00:15:41.890 --> 00:15:46.350
The formal study of love,
and desire, and attachment

00:15:46.350 --> 00:15:49.900
goes back to the early 1900s.

00:15:49.900 --> 00:15:52.607
One of the classic studies
on this is entitled

00:15:52.607 --> 00:15:53.660
"Love and Desire."

00:15:53.660 --> 00:15:56.570
It was published in
1912 and really focused

00:15:56.570 --> 00:16:00.950
on two opposing themes within romance.

00:16:00.950 --> 00:16:05.950
One is love which in that paper
was really meant to include

00:16:06.200 --> 00:16:09.440
attachment and dependence
or interdependence

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:11.660
between individuals, right?

00:16:11.660 --> 00:16:14.360
And the other end of the
spectrum being desire,

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:17.230
or the sexual desire for another.

00:16:17.230 --> 00:16:20.580
And romance was meant to
encapsulate both those things,

00:16:20.580 --> 00:16:22.330
love and desire.

00:16:22.330 --> 00:16:26.430
And for much of the 1900s,
it was thought that love

00:16:26.430 --> 00:16:30.290
and desire were on opposing
ends or in a push pull.

00:16:30.290 --> 00:16:35.290
And it was the dynamic push and
pull between love and desire

00:16:35.300 --> 00:16:38.010
that one could define romance.

00:16:38.010 --> 00:16:40.360
And that actually led to
much of what's out there

00:16:40.360 --> 00:16:42.230
in the psychological literature.

00:16:42.230 --> 00:16:46.100
Today, we are going to explore
some neurobiological studies,

00:16:46.100 --> 00:16:48.270
some studies of the endocrine system,

00:16:48.270 --> 00:16:49.470
meaning the hormone system

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:51.370
that actually support that general model.

00:16:51.370 --> 00:16:54.908
And I'll point you toward what
I think is a very useful book

00:16:54.908 --> 00:16:59.510
in thinking about how relationships
can both form and last

00:16:59.510 --> 00:17:03.230
over long periods of time
and how those relationships

00:17:03.230 --> 00:17:07.930
can include both desire
and interdependence.

00:17:07.930 --> 00:17:10.580
I'll also talk about some
studies that have really focused

00:17:10.580 --> 00:17:14.170
on why relationships
succeed and why they fail,

00:17:14.170 --> 00:17:17.320
and how that relates to whether
or not there is sufficient

00:17:17.320 --> 00:17:19.450
amounts of attachment and desire.

00:17:19.450 --> 00:17:20.780
So today we're going to
talk about the science

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:22.740
and indeed you'll also get some tools.

00:17:22.740 --> 00:17:24.400
Those tools should be useful
to you, whether or not

00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:27.190
you happen to be in a relationship or not,

00:17:27.190 --> 00:17:29.350
whether or not you're seeking
a relationship or not.

00:17:29.350 --> 00:17:30.970
I'd like to begin with an anecdote.

00:17:30.970 --> 00:17:32.350
And this is not an anecdote

00:17:32.350 --> 00:17:34.345
about my relationship history,

00:17:34.345 --> 00:17:38.120
it's an anecdote about
my scientific history.

00:17:38.120 --> 00:17:39.500
When I started graduate school,

00:17:39.500 --> 00:17:41.980
the chairman of the department
I was in at the time

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:46.980
said to me, "Most PhDs last
longer than most marriages."

00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:48.660
And indeed he was right.

00:17:48.660 --> 00:17:52.480
And also most marriages in
this country end in divorce.

00:17:52.480 --> 00:17:56.720
I think it's about 50% with a
slight skew toward more ending

00:17:56.720 --> 00:18:01.430
in divorce than persist
until death do them part.

00:18:01.430 --> 00:18:03.770
But nonetheless, it's about half,

00:18:03.770 --> 00:18:07.830
and most marriages end before
the eight-year period is up.

00:18:07.830 --> 00:18:11.700
Most PhDs take anywhere
from four to nine years.

00:18:11.700 --> 00:18:13.880
So there was a bit of a
smearing of averages there,

00:18:13.880 --> 00:18:15.180
but the point he was trying to make

00:18:15.180 --> 00:18:17.220
really landed home for me.

00:18:17.220 --> 00:18:20.300
It did not scare me out of relationships

00:18:20.300 --> 00:18:23.080
nor did it scare me out
of a PhD, obviously.

00:18:23.080 --> 00:18:26.010
What it did illustrate
was that there's something

00:18:26.010 --> 00:18:28.700
about our attachment machinery

00:18:28.700 --> 00:18:30.700
that can be very, very compelling,

00:18:30.700 --> 00:18:33.970
such that people take on
tremendous levels of commitment.

00:18:33.970 --> 00:18:36.340
I have to imagine that
most people enter marriages

00:18:36.340 --> 00:18:37.612
assuming that they're going
to stay in those marriages.

00:18:37.612 --> 00:18:40.320
I don't think most people
enter marriages thinking

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:41.510
they're going to get divorced.

00:18:41.510 --> 00:18:46.160
But that if 50% of those
commitments end in divorce,

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:47.900
there must also be mechanisms

00:18:47.900 --> 00:18:50.740
by which our attachments can break.

00:18:50.740 --> 00:18:52.860
And today we're going to
talk about both the forming

00:18:52.860 --> 00:18:55.360
of attachments and the
breaking of attachments,

00:18:55.360 --> 00:18:57.680
what can prevent those
breaks in attachments,

00:18:57.680 --> 00:19:01.040
and indeed what can
lead to re-attachments.

00:19:01.040 --> 00:19:05.940
There are biological
mechanisms to desire, love

00:19:05.940 --> 00:19:08.770
and attachment, that's abundantly clear.

00:19:08.770 --> 00:19:12.580
Now there's a robust and
very large literature

00:19:12.580 --> 00:19:13.890
in animal models.

00:19:13.890 --> 00:19:17.380
What I mean by that are field
studies and laboratory studies

00:19:17.380 --> 00:19:19.080
in primates of different kinds,

00:19:19.080 --> 00:19:22.280
such as macaque monkeys or bonobos.

00:19:22.280 --> 00:19:23.970
People have looked at
these sorts of things,

00:19:23.970 --> 00:19:26.800
believe it or not, in
ducks, in laboratory mice,

00:19:26.800 --> 00:19:29.510
in different types of birds, et cetera.

00:19:29.510 --> 00:19:32.040
And if you look at that literature,
you can essentially find

00:19:32.040 --> 00:19:36.180
biological examples in the
animal kingdom for just about

00:19:36.180 --> 00:19:39.860
any behavior that you can
easily map to human behavior.

00:19:39.860 --> 00:19:42.800
So for instance, there's
a species of animal called

00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:43.830
the prairie vole.

00:19:43.830 --> 00:19:46.350
In one portion of the United States,

00:19:46.350 --> 00:19:48.430
this prairie vole species is monogamous.

00:19:48.430 --> 00:19:51.610
They only mate with
one other prairie vole,

00:19:51.610 --> 00:19:53.570
only raise the young with
one other prairie vole

00:19:53.570 --> 00:19:55.510
for their entire life.

00:19:55.510 --> 00:19:58.157
And in another region
of the United States,

00:19:58.157 --> 00:20:01.120
the same species of animal, prairie vole,

00:20:01.120 --> 00:20:04.090
will mate with many individuals,
they're non-monogamous.

00:20:04.090 --> 00:20:06.420
And the major difference,
at least as far as we know

00:20:06.420 --> 00:20:08.430
between the prairie voles in one location

00:20:08.430 --> 00:20:11.960
and another location is
the levels of a molecule

00:20:11.960 --> 00:20:13.940
called vasopressin in the brain and body.

00:20:13.940 --> 00:20:16.010
Vasopressin is present in humans.

00:20:16.010 --> 00:20:18.410
It has numerous biological roles.

00:20:18.410 --> 00:20:20.600
It's responsible, for
instance, for controlling

00:20:20.600 --> 00:20:22.440
the amount of urine that you excrete,

00:20:22.440 --> 00:20:24.140
the amount of water that you retain,

00:20:24.140 --> 00:20:28.383
and for sexual desire,
as well as mate seeking.

00:20:29.780 --> 00:20:31.730
Levels of vasopressin in prairie voles

00:20:31.730 --> 00:20:35.460
are strongly determinant of
whether or not a prairie vole

00:20:35.460 --> 00:20:38.340
is going to be a monogamous
or non-monogamous.

00:20:38.340 --> 00:20:39.250
Why do I raise this?

00:20:39.250 --> 00:20:43.560
Well, I raise this because the
literature on prairie voles

00:20:43.560 --> 00:20:47.030
is quite beautiful and has
been discussed quite a lot

00:20:47.030 --> 00:20:47.863
in the popular press.

00:20:47.863 --> 00:20:51.010
You can look it up with an
easily, just Web Edge search.

00:20:51.010 --> 00:20:52.550
You'll find lots of
information about this,

00:20:52.550 --> 00:20:54.040
lots of news articles about this,

00:20:54.040 --> 00:20:57.120
and lots of interpretations
as to how vasopressin might

00:20:57.120 --> 00:21:00.650
be involved in similar or
different mechanisms in humans.

00:21:00.650 --> 00:21:01.956
Now, I don't have a problem

00:21:01.956 --> 00:21:04.330
with mapping animal studies to humans.

00:21:04.330 --> 00:21:05.590
I think there's certainly
a place for that.

00:21:05.590 --> 00:21:10.390
But if we just lean back
and look at the giant mass

00:21:10.390 --> 00:21:13.707
of studies in animals and
their mating behavior,

00:21:13.707 --> 00:21:15.480
and their mate selection behavior,

00:21:15.480 --> 00:21:17.870
you can essentially find
examples of anything.

00:21:17.870 --> 00:21:20.050
You can find examples of polygamy,

00:21:20.050 --> 00:21:23.450
you can find examples of
cheating, of infidelity,

00:21:23.450 --> 00:21:26.230
you can find examples of all
sorts of different behaviors

00:21:26.230 --> 00:21:29.310
that in your own mind, you
can map to human behavior.

00:21:29.310 --> 00:21:32.600
But it's really hard to make
the leap from animal models

00:21:32.600 --> 00:21:34.570
to humans in any kind of direct way.

00:21:34.570 --> 00:21:37.900
And so thankfully there's
been tremendous work done

00:21:37.900 --> 00:21:40.280
in the last mainly 20 years or so,

00:21:40.280 --> 00:21:42.500
looking at human mate selection,

00:21:42.500 --> 00:21:45.470
human desire, human love
and human attachment.

00:21:45.470 --> 00:21:47.470
So we're mainly going to
focus on those studies today,

00:21:47.470 --> 00:21:51.220
and where appropriate, we
will map those findings back

00:21:51.220 --> 00:21:54.240
to the findings in animals to
see if there's some universal

00:21:54.240 --> 00:21:56.800
truths or some universal principles

00:21:56.800 --> 00:21:58.310
about how the neural circuits

00:21:58.310 --> 00:22:00.030
and biological mechanisms work.

00:22:00.030 --> 00:22:02.340
But by and large, we're going
to focus on human studies today.

00:22:02.340 --> 00:22:04.690
So unless I say otherwise,
the data that I'm referring

00:22:04.690 --> 00:22:07.210
to today are entirely from human beings.

00:22:07.210 --> 00:22:10.240
So let's talk about attachment
and attachment styles.

00:22:10.240 --> 00:22:11.900
And this will offer you the opportunity

00:22:11.900 --> 00:22:14.323
to answer some important
questions for yourself,

00:22:15.170 --> 00:22:17.950
such as what is my, meaning,

00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:20.483
your attachment style in relationship?

00:22:21.860 --> 00:22:25.380
One of the most robust findings
in the field of psychology

00:22:25.380 --> 00:22:27.720
is this notion of attachment styles.

00:22:27.720 --> 00:22:29.660
And this was something that was discovered

00:22:29.660 --> 00:22:31.920
through a beautiful set
of studies that were done

00:22:31.920 --> 00:22:34.780
by Mary Ainsworth in the 1980s,

00:22:34.780 --> 00:22:37.280
in which she developed
a laboratory condition

00:22:37.280 --> 00:22:39.930
called the strange situation task.

00:22:39.930 --> 00:22:42.560
Now, the strange situation
task has been studied

00:22:42.560 --> 00:22:45.150
over and over again in different cultures,

00:22:45.150 --> 00:22:47.400
in different locations
throughout the world.

00:22:47.400 --> 00:22:49.620
And in preparing for this episode,

00:22:49.620 --> 00:22:51.440
I actually spoke to three
different psychologists.

00:22:51.440 --> 00:22:52.750
I spoke to a psychoanalyst,

00:22:52.750 --> 00:22:54.600
I spoke to a cognitive
behavioral psychologist,

00:22:54.600 --> 00:22:56.390
and I actually spoke to a
psychiatrist, excuse me,

00:22:56.390 --> 00:22:59.160
not a psychologist, but a
psychiatrist with a medical degree

00:22:59.160 --> 00:23:02.000
and asked, is the strange situation task

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.910
and the various attachment
styles that emerge

00:23:04.910 --> 00:23:08.290
from that task, are those
still considered valid?

00:23:08.290 --> 00:23:10.630
And indeed all three of
them said if ever there was

00:23:10.630 --> 00:23:15.120
a literature in psychology
that is absolutely tamped down

00:23:15.120 --> 00:23:20.120
and has a firm basis in both
data and real world principles

00:23:20.170 --> 00:23:22.000
and real world examples,

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:25.550
it's this notion of attachment styles.

00:23:25.550 --> 00:23:27.600
So what is the strange situation task?

00:23:27.600 --> 00:23:30.190
The strange situation
task involves a parent,

00:23:30.190 --> 00:23:32.780
typically a mother in the
studies that were done,

00:23:32.780 --> 00:23:36.930
but a parent or other
caregiver bringing their child,

00:23:36.930 --> 00:23:39.560
their actual child into a laboratory.

00:23:39.560 --> 00:23:44.190
And there's a room with a
stranger and the mother enters

00:23:44.190 --> 00:23:48.070
the room with the child and
there are some toys in the room.

00:23:48.070 --> 00:23:51.440
And typically the mother
and the stranger will talk.

00:23:51.440 --> 00:23:53.280
Obviously the stranger is
part of the experiment,

00:23:53.280 --> 00:23:55.650
is not just some random
person off the street.

00:23:55.650 --> 00:23:58.180
And the child is allowed
to move about the room.

00:23:58.180 --> 00:24:00.190
They can observe the mother interacting

00:24:00.190 --> 00:24:01.404
with the other person or not,

00:24:01.404 --> 00:24:03.510
they can play with toys or not,

00:24:03.510 --> 00:24:06.820
but then at some point the mother leaves.

00:24:06.820 --> 00:24:09.550
And then at some point later
designated by the experimenter,

00:24:09.550 --> 00:24:11.540
the mother comes back.

00:24:11.540 --> 00:24:16.540
And what is measured in these
studies is both how the child,

00:24:17.200 --> 00:24:20.073
the toddler reacts to the mother leaving,

00:24:21.010 --> 00:24:24.050
and how the child reacts
to the mother returning

00:24:24.050 --> 00:24:25.970
at the end of the experiment.

00:24:25.970 --> 00:24:29.720
And oftentimes this will have
two or three different phases

00:24:29.720 --> 00:24:32.900
where the mother will bring
the child in then leave,

00:24:32.900 --> 00:24:35.490
then come back in and leave.

00:24:35.490 --> 00:24:39.290
There are also studies in
which the behavior of the child

00:24:39.290 --> 00:24:42.120
with the stranger is also examined.

00:24:42.120 --> 00:24:43.580
So there are a lot of variations of this,

00:24:43.580 --> 00:24:48.580
but the basic findings are
that toddlers, children

00:24:49.610 --> 00:24:54.610
fall into four different
categories of attachment style.

00:24:54.790 --> 00:24:58.300
And that these attachment
styles can predict many features

00:24:58.300 --> 00:25:02.030
of adolescent, teen, young
adult, and even adult

00:25:02.030 --> 00:25:05.170
attachment styles, not
in strange situations

00:25:05.170 --> 00:25:06.690
of the sort that I just ascribed,

00:25:06.690 --> 00:25:08.623
but in romantic attachments.

00:25:10.320 --> 00:25:14.610
I should mention also that
attachment style is plastic,

00:25:14.610 --> 00:25:17.280
meaning it can change across the lifespan.

00:25:17.280 --> 00:25:19.740
So as I describe the results,
I describe the different

00:25:19.740 --> 00:25:21.603
attachment styles that are out there,

00:25:22.560 --> 00:25:27.320
and if any of those resonate
with you or bring to mind

00:25:27.320 --> 00:25:30.380
certain people in your life,
please do not assume that

00:25:30.380 --> 00:25:33.260
those attachment styles
are rigid and fixed

00:25:33.260 --> 00:25:34.280
for the entire lifespan.

00:25:34.280 --> 00:25:37.270
There are also terrific
data that indicate that

00:25:37.270 --> 00:25:40.410
through specific processes,
both psychological

00:25:40.410 --> 00:25:43.530
and some biological adjustments

00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:46.030
that people can change
their attachment style,

00:25:46.030 --> 00:25:48.620
and that indeed people who have
different attachment styles

00:25:48.620 --> 00:25:50.920
can change the attachment
styles of others.

00:25:50.920 --> 00:25:52.890
But just to make very
clear what the results

00:25:52.890 --> 00:25:55.610
of the study were, I want to
review what the four different

00:25:55.610 --> 00:25:57.840
attachment styles are,
and typically people fall

00:25:57.840 --> 00:26:01.010
into one group or another but not several.

00:26:01.010 --> 00:26:03.590
So the four patterns of
attachment that were revealed

00:26:03.590 --> 00:26:07.500
by these studies, again,
were revealed by examining

00:26:07.500 --> 00:26:10.770
the behavior of the child in
response to the mother leaving

00:26:10.770 --> 00:26:13.830
and the mother returning,
and the child's response

00:26:13.830 --> 00:26:16.720
to the stranger that is
in the room with them.

00:26:16.720 --> 00:26:21.120
The first style is the so-called
secure attachment style.

00:26:21.120 --> 00:26:23.610
In the nomenclature of this kind of study,

00:26:23.610 --> 00:26:25.130
these are the so-called B babies,

00:26:25.130 --> 00:26:27.690
as in the letter B, bulldog, B.

00:26:27.690 --> 00:26:31.010
Not for bulldogs, but just
to designate this category.

00:26:31.010 --> 00:26:35.830
The secure attachment style
is one in which the child

00:26:35.830 --> 00:26:39.080
will engage with the stranger,
with the experimenter

00:26:39.080 --> 00:26:42.330
while the parent is present in the room.

00:26:42.330 --> 00:26:44.510
But that when the parent,
typically it's a mother,

00:26:44.510 --> 00:26:47.890
but when the parent or
other caregiver leaves,

00:26:47.890 --> 00:26:50.000
the child does get visibly upset.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:51.470
They might whine, they might cry,

00:26:51.470 --> 00:26:53.490
they might even tantrum a bit.

00:26:53.490 --> 00:26:57.230
However, when the caregiver,
meaning the mother, or father,

00:26:57.230 --> 00:27:01.500
or other caregiver returns,
the child visibly expresses

00:27:01.500 --> 00:27:04.030
happiness that the caregiver
has returned, okay?

00:27:04.030 --> 00:27:07.730
So that's the hallmark of
the secure attachment style.

00:27:07.730 --> 00:27:09.243
And again, this is all pre-verbal.

00:27:09.243 --> 00:27:11.730
This is happening long
before the child can express

00:27:11.730 --> 00:27:12.993
how they feel with words.

00:27:13.850 --> 00:27:16.780
And the interpretation of
this is that the secure child

00:27:16.780 --> 00:27:19.870
feels confident that the
caregiver is available

00:27:19.870 --> 00:27:22.360
and will be responsive to their needs

00:27:22.360 --> 00:27:23.680
and their communications.

00:27:23.680 --> 00:27:28.160
So that when the child
whines and, or is distressed,

00:27:28.160 --> 00:27:29.900
the parent doesn't come
right back into the room.

00:27:29.900 --> 00:27:32.830
But at some point they do
and they seem to have a sense

00:27:32.830 --> 00:27:35.570
of trust that if the
parent or caregiver leaves

00:27:35.570 --> 00:27:37.280
that the parent will come back,

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:39.840
and that they're happy that they do.

00:27:39.840 --> 00:27:42.860
These children are also
very good at exploring

00:27:42.860 --> 00:27:45.330
novel environments after
the parent is gone,

00:27:45.330 --> 00:27:46.590
and while the parent is there.

00:27:46.590 --> 00:27:49.590
And almost always, when
the parent is there,

00:27:49.590 --> 00:27:50.841
they will explore more broadly,

00:27:50.841 --> 00:27:54.080
literally in space,
they'll venture out further

00:27:54.080 --> 00:27:56.840
than they will when the parent is gone.

00:27:56.840 --> 00:27:59.570
They also tend to engage
with the caregiver in a way

00:27:59.570 --> 00:28:01.880
that's not immediately
and completely trusting,

00:28:01.880 --> 00:28:04.610
but that over time
seems to evolve from one

00:28:04.610 --> 00:28:06.370
in which they're kind of
suspicious of this person

00:28:06.370 --> 00:28:09.890
to one in which they're at
least somewhat trusting, okay?

00:28:09.890 --> 00:28:11.980
So these were the general contours

00:28:11.980 --> 00:28:13.820
of the secure attachment style.

00:28:13.820 --> 00:28:16.600
And fortunately, nowadays
there are physiological studies

00:28:16.600 --> 00:28:18.680
measuring things like
heart rate and breathing

00:28:18.680 --> 00:28:22.440
and other measures that
correlate with the subjective

00:28:22.440 --> 00:28:25.080
assessment of what these
children are feeling.

00:28:25.080 --> 00:28:27.180
Okay, so first category
is secure attached.

00:28:27.180 --> 00:28:30.810
The second category is a
so-called anxious-avoidant

00:28:30.810 --> 00:28:35.323
or insecurely attached, which
are the category A babies.

00:28:36.200 --> 00:28:38.110
The children with
anxious-avoidant insecure

00:28:38.110 --> 00:28:41.190
attachment patterns
generally tend to avoid

00:28:41.190 --> 00:28:43.590
or ignore the caregiver, all right?

00:28:43.590 --> 00:28:47.680
Meaning the parent, and
show very little emotion

00:28:47.680 --> 00:28:51.260
when the parent leaves or returns.

00:28:51.260 --> 00:28:53.990
So this is the reason
they call them avoidant

00:28:53.990 --> 00:28:56.420
or anxious-avoidant and kind of insecure.

00:28:56.420 --> 00:28:59.390
There isn't this happiness or
joy that the parent is back.

00:28:59.390 --> 00:29:01.310
They don't seem to express that.

00:29:01.310 --> 00:29:04.570
They do not exhibit
distress on separation.

00:29:04.570 --> 00:29:09.090
And they generally tend to
have some tendency to approach

00:29:09.090 --> 00:29:11.480
the caregiver when they return,

00:29:11.480 --> 00:29:14.310
but there doesn't seem to be
a general expression of joy.

00:29:14.310 --> 00:29:16.960
And again, physiological
measures support that as well.

00:29:16.960 --> 00:29:20.730
Things like changes in heart
rate tend to be less dramatic

00:29:20.730 --> 00:29:24.250
in the anxious-avoidant
insecure attachment style

00:29:24.250 --> 00:29:25.685
than in the secure attachment style.

00:29:25.685 --> 00:29:27.743
Okay, so that's the second one.

00:29:28.750 --> 00:29:30.700
The third category is the so-called

00:29:30.700 --> 00:29:35.430
anxious-ambivalent/resistant-insecure
category.

00:29:35.430 --> 00:29:36.750
Okay, I didn't name these categories.

00:29:36.750 --> 00:29:39.860
So you have to blame others
in this one instance.

00:29:39.860 --> 00:29:41.880
For everything else blame
me, but in this instance,

00:29:41.880 --> 00:29:43.147
you have to blame the psychologists

00:29:43.147 --> 00:29:44.910
that named this category.

00:29:44.910 --> 00:29:48.700
The anxious-ambivalent/resistant-insecure
category

00:29:48.700 --> 00:29:51.040
also called the C babies,

00:29:51.040 --> 00:29:54.050
for the letter C just as a categorization.

00:29:54.050 --> 00:29:58.810
The anxious-ambivalent,
resistant-insecure toddlers, really,

00:29:58.810 --> 00:30:01.970
show distress even before
separation from their mother

00:30:01.970 --> 00:30:03.190
or other caregiver.

00:30:03.190 --> 00:30:06.450
And they tend to be very
clingy and difficult to comfort

00:30:06.450 --> 00:30:09.080
when the caregiver returns, okay?

00:30:09.080 --> 00:30:12.210
So they're distressed even
before the mother leaves the room

00:30:12.210 --> 00:30:15.430
and they tend to be very clingy
and really hard to calm down

00:30:15.430 --> 00:30:16.630
when the mother returns.

00:30:18.250 --> 00:30:21.590
They tend to show either
what seems to be resentment

00:30:21.590 --> 00:30:23.480
in response to the parent's absence.

00:30:23.480 --> 00:30:24.950
We don't really know what they're feeling.

00:30:24.950 --> 00:30:26.970
Or some helpless passivity.

00:30:26.970 --> 00:30:28.270
And there's actually subcategorizations

00:30:28.270 --> 00:30:31.180
that the psychologists have
come up with, C one subtypes

00:30:31.180 --> 00:30:32.013
and C two subtypes.

00:30:32.013 --> 00:30:33.590
We don't have to get bogged down in that.

00:30:33.590 --> 00:30:37.000
But just know that there
isn't one absolute measure

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:39.220
that says, oh, well, this person

00:30:39.220 --> 00:30:41.660
is anxious-ambivalent, resistant-insecure.

00:30:41.660 --> 00:30:45.530
They could be somewhat
passive, or they could be,

00:30:45.530 --> 00:30:47.770
seem somewhat angry at the caregiver.

00:30:47.770 --> 00:30:52.770
But the basic idea is that
before and after the separation,

00:30:52.810 --> 00:30:55.280
they are clingy and difficult to comfort.

00:30:55.280 --> 00:30:56.970
They just can't seem to
calm themselves down,

00:30:56.970 --> 00:30:59.560
and physiological measures
of heart rate and hormone

00:30:59.560 --> 00:31:02.840
measurements such as cortisol
also support that statement.

00:31:02.840 --> 00:31:06.700
And the third category of
attachment style is the so-called

00:31:06.700 --> 00:31:11.160
disorganized or disoriented
or D for the letter D babies.

00:31:11.160 --> 00:31:13.750
This is a categorization
that was added later

00:31:13.750 --> 00:31:15.620
to this strange situation task.

00:31:15.620 --> 00:31:19.410
That is a real hallmark of
developmental psychology studies.

00:31:19.410 --> 00:31:23.320
It was developed by Mary
Ainsworth, graduate student,

00:31:23.320 --> 00:31:26.110
Mary Maine, who I actually had
the great fortune of taking

00:31:26.110 --> 00:31:27.970
a course from and learning
from when I was a graduate

00:31:27.970 --> 00:31:30.690
student at Berkeley many years ago.

00:31:30.690 --> 00:31:32.820
And this fourth categorization
was controversial

00:31:32.820 --> 00:31:35.750
for a while, but now
is generally accepted.

00:31:35.750 --> 00:31:40.170
The key feature of the
disorganized, disoriented category

00:31:40.170 --> 00:31:43.480
is that the toddlers tend to be tense

00:31:43.480 --> 00:31:47.610
and they tend to encompass a
lot of odd physical postures.

00:31:47.610 --> 00:31:49.970
They tend to hunch their shoulders.

00:31:49.970 --> 00:31:51.720
They'll put their hands behind their neck.

00:31:51.720 --> 00:31:54.240
They'll cock their head to the side.

00:31:54.240 --> 00:31:55.150
For those of you listening,

00:31:55.150 --> 00:31:56.750
I'm doing this on the video version.

00:31:56.750 --> 00:31:59.020
It's not where you don't
have to go see that.

00:31:59.020 --> 00:32:01.480
But for those of you that
are watching this on video,

00:32:01.480 --> 00:32:04.340
they tend to constrain
their body size a bit

00:32:04.340 --> 00:32:07.110
and going to odd postures
that they normally wouldn't

00:32:08.040 --> 00:32:09.363
do anywhere else.

00:32:10.410 --> 00:32:12.530
So this is why it's
called the disorganized

00:32:12.530 --> 00:32:15.060
or disoriented category.

00:32:15.060 --> 00:32:17.190
It seems like these children
just don't really know

00:32:17.190 --> 00:32:19.130
how to react to a separation.

00:32:19.130 --> 00:32:22.380
And they just start to manifest
behaviors and emotional

00:32:22.380 --> 00:32:25.710
tones that aren't observed
in other situations.

00:32:25.710 --> 00:32:27.830
Okay, so we've got our four categories.

00:32:27.830 --> 00:32:29.550
I'll try and use the
shortest possible names

00:32:29.550 --> 00:32:30.383
for each category.

00:32:30.383 --> 00:32:32.670
We've got category one,
which is securely attached.

00:32:32.670 --> 00:32:35.760
We've got category two,
which is insecurely attached,

00:32:35.760 --> 00:32:38.170
also sometimes called anxious-avoidant.

00:32:38.170 --> 00:32:39.560
Then we've got category three,

00:32:39.560 --> 00:32:42.750
which is the resistant-insecure category,

00:32:42.750 --> 00:32:44.090
which is anxious-ambivalent.

00:32:44.090 --> 00:32:45.870
And then there's this fourth category,

00:32:45.870 --> 00:32:48.450
the disorganized, disoriented category

00:32:48.450 --> 00:32:50.950
where they're so-called D babies.

00:32:50.950 --> 00:32:54.730
Now, what's interesting about
this from the perspective

00:32:54.730 --> 00:32:59.730
of desire, love and attachment
is that the categorizations

00:32:59.940 --> 00:33:03.520
of children into one of these
four different categories

00:33:03.520 --> 00:33:08.310
as toddlers is strongly predictive
of their attachment style

00:33:08.310 --> 00:33:11.310
in romantic partnerships later in life.

00:33:11.310 --> 00:33:14.930
Which is to me both amazing and surprising

00:33:14.930 --> 00:33:17.100
and not surprising all at the same time.

00:33:17.100 --> 00:33:20.920
Amazing because it means
that, first of all,

00:33:20.920 --> 00:33:23.720
we are relatively
hardwired for attachment.

00:33:23.720 --> 00:33:26.680
I think that that's
incredible and beautiful,

00:33:26.680 --> 00:33:29.700
that we have designated
neurons, nerve cells

00:33:29.700 --> 00:33:32.650
and hormonal systems
that are there to ensure

00:33:32.650 --> 00:33:37.090
that we have some response
to a caregiver being there,

00:33:37.090 --> 00:33:40.210
or not being there, or
returning, or leaving,

00:33:40.210 --> 00:33:43.860
but also that the same neural
circuitries, the same hormonal

00:33:43.860 --> 00:33:47.440
responses are at least
in some way repurposed

00:33:47.440 --> 00:33:51.300
for entirely different types
of attachments later in life.

00:33:51.300 --> 00:33:56.290
So when we hear the psychologist
talk about how we formed

00:33:56.290 --> 00:33:58.800
a template early in life
based on experiences

00:33:58.800 --> 00:34:01.550
that were even pre-verbal
before we had language,

00:34:01.550 --> 00:34:05.330
and those templates are
superimposed on our relationships,

00:34:05.330 --> 00:34:08.120
or we should say, our later
relationships are superimposed

00:34:08.120 --> 00:34:10.690
on those templates, there
really is a basis for that.

00:34:10.690 --> 00:34:14.070
We now have neuroimaging studies
to support, for instance,

00:34:14.070 --> 00:34:17.920
the work of Allan Schore
from UCLA, showing that

00:34:17.920 --> 00:34:21.870
when a mother and child
interact, either through very

00:34:21.870 --> 00:34:24.080
soothing interactions,
like bottle feeding,

00:34:24.080 --> 00:34:26.930
or breastfeeding, or
singing to one's baby,

00:34:26.930 --> 00:34:30.320
or putting them to sleep,
that the brain of the child

00:34:30.320 --> 00:34:31.610
and the brain of the mother

00:34:31.610 --> 00:34:34.680
are entering a coordinated
state of relaxation.

00:34:34.680 --> 00:34:36.960
And it's not one
direction, mother to child,

00:34:36.960 --> 00:34:39.303
the child is also calming the mother.

00:34:40.450 --> 00:34:42.380
Typically these studies were
done with mothers again,

00:34:42.380 --> 00:34:45.150
sometimes with fathers,
but typically with mothers.

00:34:45.150 --> 00:34:49.020
And in addition to that, when
the mother or other caregiver

00:34:49.020 --> 00:34:51.930
acts very excited and raises their voice,

00:34:51.930 --> 00:34:54.820
or puts a lilt in their
voice, or widens their eyes,

00:34:54.820 --> 00:34:56.116
that the child will do the same.

00:34:56.116 --> 00:34:59.110
And again, there's a
bidirectional interaction

00:34:59.110 --> 00:35:01.150
in that case of excitement.

00:35:01.150 --> 00:35:03.960
And there's the release of
neurochemicals like dopamine

00:35:03.960 --> 00:35:06.640
into the bloodstream, whereas
in the relaxation scenario

00:35:06.640 --> 00:35:09.560
and the soothing scenario,
there's we know the release

00:35:09.560 --> 00:35:11.850
of things like serotonin and oxytocin.

00:35:11.850 --> 00:35:16.850
So the neural systems for
attachment and the neural systems

00:35:16.880 --> 00:35:21.460
for what we call autonomic
arousal for being alert and calm

00:35:21.460 --> 00:35:23.740
don't act in a vacuum.

00:35:23.740 --> 00:35:26.420
They are tethered to other
people in our environment.

00:35:26.420 --> 00:35:27.930
And of course we know this, right?

00:35:27.930 --> 00:35:29.170
We sometimes hear the statement,

00:35:29.170 --> 00:35:30.780
no one can make you feel anything.

00:35:30.780 --> 00:35:32.000
I've always had a little bit of a problem

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:33.000
with that statement.

00:35:34.020 --> 00:35:36.890
I don't think I'm contradicting
anyone in particular,

00:35:36.890 --> 00:35:39.430
but you hear that a lot, no
one can make you feel anything.

00:35:39.430 --> 00:35:40.620
Indeed they can, right?

00:35:40.620 --> 00:35:43.270
A physical injury can
make you feel something.

00:35:43.270 --> 00:35:45.490
If somebody says something
that you very much like,

00:35:45.490 --> 00:35:46.387
it can make you feel something.

00:35:46.387 --> 00:35:49.330
And if somebody says something
that you very much dislike,

00:35:49.330 --> 00:35:50.610
it will make you feel something.

00:35:50.610 --> 00:35:52.970
So the idea that no one
can make us feel anything

00:35:52.970 --> 00:35:54.090
isn't actually true.

00:35:54.090 --> 00:35:56.400
Our nervous system is tethered

00:35:56.400 --> 00:35:57.959
to the nervous systems of others.

00:35:57.959 --> 00:36:01.560
And that is true from the very
earliest stages of our lives.

00:36:01.560 --> 00:36:04.340
And in this case, we're
talking about how our templates

00:36:04.340 --> 00:36:08.110
for attachment in romantic
relationships, how we find them,

00:36:08.110 --> 00:36:10.400
how we maintain them, and
indeed how we break them

00:36:10.400 --> 00:36:14.330
and reform them is based on a
template that was established

00:36:14.330 --> 00:36:16.610
through an entirely
different set of priorities,

00:36:16.610 --> 00:36:20.390
which was how we feel safe and
secure in novel environments,

00:36:20.390 --> 00:36:22.260
depending on whether or
not our primary caregiver

00:36:22.260 --> 00:36:23.270
is there or not.

00:36:23.270 --> 00:36:24.930
Neuroimaging supports that.

00:36:24.930 --> 00:36:27.460
When I say neuroimaging, I
mean, brain scan support that,

00:36:27.460 --> 00:36:30.140
measures of hormones in the
body and brain support that,

00:36:30.140 --> 00:36:32.060
measures of neurochemicals support that.

00:36:32.060 --> 00:36:34.290
There's simply no way around this truth,

00:36:34.290 --> 00:36:38.390
that we have a set of roadmaps
in our mind that are reused

00:36:38.390 --> 00:36:41.210
for entirely different
purposes later in life.

00:36:41.210 --> 00:36:43.770
That is vitally important to understand.

00:36:43.770 --> 00:36:47.760
Because if one is successful in forming

00:36:47.760 --> 00:36:52.760
romantic attachments, maintaining
them, et cetera, or not,

00:36:52.860 --> 00:36:55.880
does in fact reflect the earlier templates

00:36:55.880 --> 00:36:57.130
that you've created.

00:36:57.130 --> 00:36:59.540
But as I've mentioned
before, the good news is

00:36:59.540 --> 00:37:01.660
that these templates can shift over time.

00:37:01.660 --> 00:37:04.210
And one of the more powerful
ways to shift those templates

00:37:04.210 --> 00:37:07.990
over time is purely by the
knowledge that they exist,

00:37:07.990 --> 00:37:11.920
and the understanding that
those templates are malleable.

00:37:11.920 --> 00:37:15.640
They can change through the
process of neuroplasticity.

00:37:15.640 --> 00:37:17.590
Again, neuroplasticity is just a rewiring

00:37:17.590 --> 00:37:19.030
of nerve connection.

00:37:19.030 --> 00:37:21.760
That is very much present in childhood,

00:37:21.760 --> 00:37:23.950
but also very much present in adulthood.

00:37:23.950 --> 00:37:27.210
So if you're somebody who
you think falls into category

00:37:27.210 --> 00:37:29.890
one, two, three, or four,
or you know somebody,

00:37:29.890 --> 00:37:31.960
or involved with somebody
who falls into category

00:37:31.960 --> 00:37:33.283
one, two, three, and four,

00:37:34.730 --> 00:37:37.150
the mere knowledge of
that can be very useful.

00:37:37.150 --> 00:37:39.160
But you might ask, well, what
do I do with that knowledge?

00:37:39.160 --> 00:37:41.410
Well, fortunately, both
psychologists and biologists

00:37:41.410 --> 00:37:44.830
have started to leverage that
knowledge toward establishing

00:37:44.830 --> 00:37:48.320
better, more secure bonds in
adult romantic relationships.

00:37:48.320 --> 00:37:51.270
And there's a book that has
really tapped into this.

00:37:51.270 --> 00:37:53.030
I think it's the first book
that has really addressed

00:37:53.030 --> 00:37:53.910
this head on.

00:37:53.910 --> 00:37:57.483
And that book comes from
two Columbia professors.

00:37:58.750 --> 00:38:03.750
And title of the book is
"Attached: The New Science of Adult

00:38:03.830 --> 00:38:07.090
Attachment and How It Can
Help You Find and Keep Love."

00:38:07.090 --> 00:38:11.220
The authors of this book are
Amir Levine and Rachel Heller.

00:38:11.220 --> 00:38:15.070
Again, both of them are skilled
academics and researchers

00:38:15.070 --> 00:38:17.700
who have really taken the
literature that I described

00:38:17.700 --> 00:38:19.080
on the strange situation task

00:38:19.080 --> 00:38:21.120
and mapped it to adult attachment styles.

00:38:21.120 --> 00:38:24.920
And also they've mapped out
ways that they've observed

00:38:24.920 --> 00:38:26.280
in their clinical practice.

00:38:26.280 --> 00:38:30.520
And that is laboratory
supported for, for instance,

00:38:30.520 --> 00:38:32.580
people that have an anxious-ambivalent

00:38:32.580 --> 00:38:34.850
or what we were calling
insecure attachment style,

00:38:34.850 --> 00:38:36.470
or for people that fall

00:38:36.470 --> 00:38:39.830
into the disorganized or
disoriented attachment style,

00:38:39.830 --> 00:38:43.300
how they can modify that
attachment style in or out

00:38:43.300 --> 00:38:46.700
of relationships in order
to establish what I think

00:38:46.700 --> 00:38:48.910
everybody wants, which
is secure attachment.

00:38:48.910 --> 00:38:50.130
Why does everybody want that?

00:38:50.130 --> 00:38:52.930
Well, secure attachment
allows people to be both

00:38:52.930 --> 00:38:56.190
in relationship, or if they
choose to be on their own,

00:38:56.190 --> 00:38:58.770
or to be in relationship
but physically separated

00:38:58.770 --> 00:39:00.770
from somebody else, or
even emotionally separated

00:39:00.770 --> 00:39:02.565
from somebody else and maintain

00:39:02.565 --> 00:39:05.550
what we call a stable
autonomic equilibrium,

00:39:05.550 --> 00:39:08.320
the ability to remain calm, clearheaded.

00:39:08.320 --> 00:39:10.010
You might not like what's happening,

00:39:10.010 --> 00:39:12.700
but you're able to navigate
that with some sense of clarity

00:39:12.700 --> 00:39:14.770
and not excessive discomfort.

00:39:14.770 --> 00:39:17.280
So, is there a goal in all of this stuff

00:39:17.280 --> 00:39:19.330
about love, desire, and attachment?

00:39:19.330 --> 00:39:20.610
Indeed, there is.

00:39:20.610 --> 00:39:24.500
The secure attachment
style is the one that leads

00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:28.140
to the most stable and predictable
long-term relationships.

00:39:28.140 --> 00:39:32.730
Put differently, babies,
toddlers, adolescents, teens,

00:39:32.730 --> 00:39:35.350
and young adults that have
a secure attachment style

00:39:35.350 --> 00:39:38.520
are more likely to find and
form long-term relationships

00:39:38.520 --> 00:39:40.820
than are people in the other categories.

00:39:40.820 --> 00:39:44.560
But people in other categories
can learn and eventually

00:39:44.560 --> 00:39:47.690
migrate into the secure attachment style.

00:39:47.690 --> 00:39:49.960
And I think that book "Attached..."

00:39:49.960 --> 00:39:52.580
I have no affiliation to the
authors or the book itself,

00:39:52.580 --> 00:39:53.617
I should just mention that.

00:39:53.617 --> 00:39:55.820
"Attached: The New Science
of Adult Attachment

00:39:55.820 --> 00:39:57.530
and How It Can Help You
Find and Keep Love,"

00:39:57.530 --> 00:40:00.770
really it sounds very pop psychology, yes,

00:40:00.770 --> 00:40:02.040
but it is really grounded

00:40:02.040 --> 00:40:03.880
in the research psychology literature.

00:40:03.880 --> 00:40:06.950
And there's also some
interesting biology there.

00:40:06.950 --> 00:40:09.810
Another point to make
about attachment styles

00:40:09.810 --> 00:40:12.350
is that it is possible.

00:40:12.350 --> 00:40:14.940
And some of you may be
familiar with circumstances

00:40:14.940 --> 00:40:18.120
whereby people who are securely attached,

00:40:18.120 --> 00:40:19.930
either because they grew
up in an environment

00:40:19.930 --> 00:40:22.110
where secure attachment was cultivated,

00:40:22.110 --> 00:40:24.610
or because they developed
that on their own,

00:40:24.610 --> 00:40:29.010
can also migrate out of the
securely attached category

00:40:29.010 --> 00:40:32.700
into insecurely attached,
or into avoidant types

00:40:32.700 --> 00:40:36.330
of attachment styles as
teens, or as young adults,

00:40:36.330 --> 00:40:40.760
or as adults at any age
or any stage of life,

00:40:40.760 --> 00:40:43.800
by virtue of being with
somebody who has a different,

00:40:43.800 --> 00:40:47.310
perhaps less adaptive
attachment style, right?

00:40:47.310 --> 00:40:50.440
What this means is that
if you have or you develop

00:40:50.440 --> 00:40:53.760
a secure attachment style,
it's vitally important

00:40:53.760 --> 00:40:56.690
to protect that attachment
style because it is possible

00:40:56.690 --> 00:40:57.776
to become anxiously attached,

00:40:57.776 --> 00:41:01.210
even if you grew up in a
stable attachment framework.

00:41:01.210 --> 00:41:03.700
And again, this can happen at any stage.

00:41:03.700 --> 00:41:05.510
So if you're interested
in attachment styles

00:41:05.510 --> 00:41:08.700
and how they influence
adult romantic attachments,

00:41:08.700 --> 00:41:12.050
and certainly if you are a
parent, I would encourage you

00:41:12.050 --> 00:41:14.890
to check out the book, "Attached."

00:41:14.890 --> 00:41:17.460
Again, it's quite good and I
think that it offers a number

00:41:17.460 --> 00:41:20.087
of actionable tools to both form

00:41:20.087 --> 00:41:22.500
and hold onto secure attachment styles.

00:41:22.500 --> 00:41:25.820
So I mentioned that the neural
circuits for child-parent

00:41:25.820 --> 00:41:29.490
or child-caregiver
attachment are repurposed

00:41:29.490 --> 00:41:32.460
for romantic attachment later in life.

00:41:32.460 --> 00:41:34.830
But what are these neural circuits?

00:41:34.830 --> 00:41:35.770
What do they do?

00:41:35.770 --> 00:41:39.150
I mean, it's so attractive, if you will,

00:41:39.150 --> 00:41:41.700
to think about a brain
area that controls love,

00:41:41.700 --> 00:41:43.780
or a brain area that controls desire,

00:41:43.780 --> 00:41:45.390
or a brain area that controls attachment,

00:41:45.390 --> 00:41:47.250
but it simply doesn't work that way.

00:41:47.250 --> 00:41:49.520
As I've talked about
before on this podcast

00:41:49.520 --> 00:41:51.800
and I will say again and
again because it will persist

00:41:51.800 --> 00:41:53.900
to be true long after I'm gone,

00:41:53.900 --> 00:41:57.910
is that no one brain area
can give rise to anything

00:41:57.910 --> 00:42:01.070
as complex as desire,
or love, or attachment.

00:42:01.070 --> 00:42:03.640
Instead, there are
multiple brain areas that

00:42:03.640 --> 00:42:06.060
through their coordinated action create

00:42:06.060 --> 00:42:09.970
a song that we call desire,
or a song that we call love,

00:42:09.970 --> 00:42:11.260
or a song that we call attachment.

00:42:11.260 --> 00:42:13.820
Not a literal song,
although there are songs

00:42:13.820 --> 00:42:16.380
about desire, love, and
attachment, of course, many songs,

00:42:16.380 --> 00:42:19.150
some good, some not so good.

00:42:19.150 --> 00:42:22.750
But rather different brain
areas being active in different

00:42:22.750 --> 00:42:26.270
sequences and with different
intensities can make us feel

00:42:26.270 --> 00:42:29.560
as if we are in the mode
that we call desire,

00:42:29.560 --> 00:42:32.600
or in the mode of love, or
in the mode of attachment.

00:42:32.600 --> 00:42:36.410
But beneath all of that is this element

00:42:36.410 --> 00:42:37.920
of autonomic arousal.

00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:40.450
And I want to focus on autonomic arousal

00:42:40.450 --> 00:42:41.500
just for a bit longer,

00:42:41.500 --> 00:42:45.270
because it really is one
of the three core elements

00:42:45.270 --> 00:42:48.670
by which we form and
maintain loving attachments,

00:42:48.670 --> 00:42:51.413
and by which we break loving attachments.

00:42:52.360 --> 00:42:54.010
The autonomic nervous system

00:42:54.010 --> 00:42:57.100
as the name suggests is automatic.

00:42:57.100 --> 00:42:59.080
In fact, that's what autonomic means.

00:42:59.080 --> 00:43:01.860
Now it's actually the
case that we can control

00:43:01.860 --> 00:43:04.190
our autonomic nervous system
to some degree or another.

00:43:04.190 --> 00:43:06.800
But the autonomic nervous
system controls things like

00:43:06.800 --> 00:43:10.470
digestion, our breathing,
whether or not we're conscious

00:43:10.470 --> 00:43:11.910
of that breathing or not.

00:43:11.910 --> 00:43:15.970
It controls things like how
alert we are or sleepy we are.

00:43:15.970 --> 00:43:18.120
And the autonomic nervous system,

00:43:18.120 --> 00:43:19.960
as I just briefly described earlier,

00:43:19.960 --> 00:43:22.730
is really something that we
come into the world with.

00:43:22.730 --> 00:43:25.470
It's hardwired, all
the elements are there.

00:43:25.470 --> 00:43:28.460
But through interactions with our parent,

00:43:28.460 --> 00:43:32.780
either soothing interactions,
or fun, playful interactions,

00:43:32.780 --> 00:43:35.520
or dare I say, scary interactions,

00:43:35.520 --> 00:43:38.740
our autonomic nervous
system gets tuned up.

00:43:38.740 --> 00:43:42.687
Meaning, we each develop a
tendency to either be more alert

00:43:42.687 --> 00:43:47.070
and anxious, or more calm, or
a balance of alert and calm.

00:43:47.070 --> 00:43:49.060
Now, of course, this
changes across each day

00:43:49.060 --> 00:43:50.770
and depending how tired
we are late in the day.

00:43:50.770 --> 00:43:51.680
If we've been awake for a while,

00:43:51.680 --> 00:43:53.360
we tend to get sleepy early in the day.

00:43:53.360 --> 00:43:54.200
If we're very rested,

00:43:54.200 --> 00:43:56.290
we tend to wake up and feel very alert.

00:43:56.290 --> 00:43:57.960
So the way to think about
the autonomic nervous system

00:43:57.960 --> 00:43:59.520
is it's kind of a seesaw.

00:43:59.520 --> 00:44:02.170
We go back and forth
between being very alert,

00:44:02.170 --> 00:44:04.800
we can be alert and calm, or
we can be very, very alert,

00:44:04.800 --> 00:44:06.260
we can be in a state of panic,

00:44:06.260 --> 00:44:09.250
we can be fast asleep so
we can be extremely calm,

00:44:09.250 --> 00:44:14.250
or we can just be sleepy, semi
calm but still also alert.

00:44:14.900 --> 00:44:17.030
So think about it like a seesaw.

00:44:17.030 --> 00:44:19.970
And that seesaw has a hinge,

00:44:19.970 --> 00:44:23.270
and that hinge defines how
tight or loose that seesaw is,

00:44:23.270 --> 00:44:26.140
how readily it can tilt back and forth.

00:44:26.140 --> 00:44:30.160
Our autonomic tone is
how tight that hinge is.

00:44:30.160 --> 00:44:32.180
And there are biological
mechanisms to explain this,

00:44:32.180 --> 00:44:33.800
but here I just want to
stay with the analogy

00:44:33.800 --> 00:44:35.063
of the seesaw for now.

00:44:36.720 --> 00:44:41.720
The interactions between child
and caregiver early in life

00:44:41.910 --> 00:44:44.290
take the child and the caregiver

00:44:44.290 --> 00:44:47.060
from one end of the seesaw to the other.

00:44:47.060 --> 00:44:50.170
From being very alert in a
state of play, for instance,

00:44:50.170 --> 00:44:53.490
to being nursed and being very
soothed until we go to sleep.

00:44:53.490 --> 00:44:55.980
And of course, we each have a seesaw,

00:44:55.980 --> 00:44:57.117
the parent and the child has a seesaw,

00:44:57.117 --> 00:44:58.200
and they're interacting.

00:44:58.200 --> 00:44:59.106
What do I mean by that?

00:44:59.106 --> 00:45:03.000
Well, there are beautiful
studies, and beautiful

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:05.280
not in the sense that they
focused on a pleasant topic,

00:45:05.280 --> 00:45:08.430
but beautiful because they
were done so beautifully well,

00:45:08.430 --> 00:45:12.520
that looked at, for instance,
the response of mothers

00:45:12.520 --> 00:45:15.080
and their physiologies and
the response of children

00:45:15.080 --> 00:45:18.500
and their physiologies
during the bombing of cities

00:45:18.500 --> 00:45:19.560
during World War II.

00:45:19.560 --> 00:45:21.540
So an unpleasant situation.

00:45:21.540 --> 00:45:25.140
But what was revealed during
the course of these studies

00:45:25.140 --> 00:45:28.750
was that if the mothers were very stressed

00:45:28.750 --> 00:45:31.580
during an onslaught of
bombing of the city,

00:45:31.580 --> 00:45:34.930
the children's physiologies
tended to be stressed also,

00:45:34.930 --> 00:45:38.810
and persisted in being stressed
long after that stressful

00:45:38.810 --> 00:45:41.600
episode was done.

00:45:41.600 --> 00:45:43.690
They actually followed that these children

00:45:43.690 --> 00:45:47.400
well out from many decades afterwards.

00:45:47.400 --> 00:45:50.850
Conversely, if the parent,
and in this case, again,

00:45:50.850 --> 00:45:53.730
it was mothers that were
explored in these studies,

00:45:53.730 --> 00:45:55.810
had turned this whole business of going

00:45:55.810 --> 00:45:59.130
into the bomb shelters into
somewhat of a game, right?

00:45:59.130 --> 00:46:01.627
Taking it seriously, but
essentially telling the children,

00:46:01.627 --> 00:46:02.460
"Okay, it's time to go,"

00:46:02.460 --> 00:46:05.860
but not expressing much
stress or distress,

00:46:05.860 --> 00:46:07.156
the children also didn't
develop much stress,

00:46:07.156 --> 00:46:09.400
or distress, or trauma.

00:46:09.400 --> 00:46:10.980
Now there were exceptions
to this, of course,

00:46:10.980 --> 00:46:12.162
but in general, that was the rule

00:46:12.162 --> 00:46:15.620
that the autonomic nervous
systems of children tend to mimic

00:46:15.620 --> 00:46:18.800
the autonomic nervous systems
of the primary caregiver.

00:46:18.800 --> 00:46:22.630
And the mechanisms by which
this occurs has been explored.

00:46:22.630 --> 00:46:25.620
And again I just refer to the
beautiful work of Allan Schore

00:46:25.620 --> 00:46:28.140
at University of California, Los Angeles.

00:46:28.140 --> 00:46:32.387
And again, his name is
Schore, spelled S-C-H-O-R-E.

00:46:32.387 --> 00:46:33.940
I'm looking down briefly at the floor here

00:46:33.940 --> 00:46:36.630
because I'll just reach for the book.

00:46:36.630 --> 00:46:39.730
He has a wonderful book called
"Right Brain Psychotherapy."

00:46:39.730 --> 00:46:40.760
It's a little bit technical,

00:46:40.760 --> 00:46:43.210
but if you're interested
in some of the studies,

00:46:43.210 --> 00:46:46.290
this book "Right Brain
Psychotherapy" details how everything

00:46:46.290 --> 00:46:50.320
from nursing of children
to playtime behavior,

00:46:50.320 --> 00:46:53.260
to strange situation type
task behavior that we talked

00:46:53.260 --> 00:46:55.310
about before which of
course occurs when children

00:46:55.310 --> 00:46:57.177
get dropped off at
daycare, or nursery school,

00:46:57.177 --> 00:46:59.600
or with babysitters, et cetera.

00:46:59.600 --> 00:47:04.080
And indeed all types of
caregiver-child interactions

00:47:04.080 --> 00:47:06.910
tune up that autonomic nervous system,

00:47:06.910 --> 00:47:10.220
so that the child ends up with
an autonomic nervous system

00:47:10.220 --> 00:47:14.720
that either tends to lean more
towards alert and anxious,

00:47:14.720 --> 00:47:16.580
or can be very alert but calm,

00:47:16.580 --> 00:47:18.440
or can be very calm and hard to budge.

00:47:18.440 --> 00:47:20.820
Again, it's the tightness of that hinge

00:47:20.820 --> 00:47:23.770
that really underlies
these attachment styles

00:47:23.770 --> 00:47:25.270
that we were talking about earlier,

00:47:25.270 --> 00:47:28.030
and not on this episode of
the "Huberman Lab Podcast,"

00:47:28.030 --> 00:47:29.620
but on many other previous
previous episodes,

00:47:29.620 --> 00:47:31.730
such as the master stress episode,

00:47:31.730 --> 00:47:34.670
or some of the optimized health episodes.

00:47:34.670 --> 00:47:36.970
You can find these if you
want at hubermanlab.com.

00:47:36.970 --> 00:47:40.240
A lot of the tools and techniques
that are recommended there

00:47:40.240 --> 00:47:43.890
have to do with readjusting
the autonomic nervous system

00:47:43.890 --> 00:47:45.265
in deliberate ways as an adult.

00:47:45.265 --> 00:47:48.610
Again, I won't go into the specific tools,

00:47:48.610 --> 00:47:52.660
but for instance, the physiological sigh.

00:47:52.660 --> 00:47:56.280
This tool that I've talked
about extensively of two inhales

00:47:56.280 --> 00:47:58.890
through the nose, as deeply
as you can on the first one,

00:47:58.890 --> 00:48:00.170
sneaking in a little bit
more air on the second one,

00:48:00.170 --> 00:48:02.910
and then a long exhale through the mouth

00:48:02.910 --> 00:48:05.680
is a way of adjusting
that autonomic seesaw.

00:48:05.680 --> 00:48:07.340
It tends to make us more calm.

00:48:07.340 --> 00:48:10.470
It activates what we call
the parasympathetic arm

00:48:10.470 --> 00:48:12.970
of the autonomic nervous
system, which is just fancy nerd

00:48:12.970 --> 00:48:16.290
speak for it's a quick way
to calm yourself down, right?

00:48:16.290 --> 00:48:20.680
Things like ice baths, or cold
showers, or cold immersion,

00:48:20.680 --> 00:48:24.610
or deliberate
hyperventilation by contrast,

00:48:24.610 --> 00:48:28.280
or ways in which we can
deliberately increase the level

00:48:28.280 --> 00:48:30.967
of our so-called sympathetic
arm of our autonomic nervous

00:48:30.967 --> 00:48:32.870
system to make ourselves more alert.

00:48:32.870 --> 00:48:33.910
Why would you want to do that?

00:48:33.910 --> 00:48:35.840
Well, you can do that to be more alert,

00:48:35.840 --> 00:48:37.280
to be more awake, if you like,

00:48:37.280 --> 00:48:40.500
or as a form of self-induced
stress inoculation

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:43.770
to be able to tolerate
higher levels of adrenaline

00:48:43.770 --> 00:48:46.353
by making it a practice
that you self-direct.

00:48:47.390 --> 00:48:51.510
The reason those tools are out
there is because many of us,

00:48:51.510 --> 00:48:54.380
for whatever reason, we
don't have to blame anyone,

00:48:54.380 --> 00:48:56.880
but because of our childhood templates,

00:48:56.880 --> 00:48:58.770
because of things that
happened and didn't happen

00:48:58.770 --> 00:49:00.760
in terms of our interactions
with caregivers,

00:49:00.760 --> 00:49:03.370
have autonomic nervous systems
that are tilted to one side

00:49:03.370 --> 00:49:05.400
or the other more than we would like.

00:49:05.400 --> 00:49:10.320
Or in which the hinge that I'm
talking about in this analogy

00:49:10.320 --> 00:49:13.030
is too loose or that is too tight.

00:49:13.030 --> 00:49:15.010
And we're stuck in a mode of anxiousness,

00:49:15.010 --> 00:49:17.180
or stuck in a mode of lack of energy.

00:49:17.180 --> 00:49:19.560
That's what those tools are really about.

00:49:19.560 --> 00:49:24.560
But at a deeper level, the
autonomic nervous system

00:49:24.660 --> 00:49:27.900
is really the system that
governs how we will react

00:49:27.900 --> 00:49:32.900
in response to a romantic
partner being present or leaving.

00:49:33.410 --> 00:49:35.680
And I don't necessarily mean
leaving the relationship

00:49:35.680 --> 00:49:37.790
entirely, although it
could mean that, right?

00:49:37.790 --> 00:49:41.210
We know people, I'm sure you
know people that upon the end

00:49:41.210 --> 00:49:43.470
of a relationship that
they wanted very much,

00:49:43.470 --> 00:49:44.990
are absolutely crushed.

00:49:44.990 --> 00:49:47.242
And actually in researching
this episode there,

00:49:47.242 --> 00:49:50.220
I discovered there's an
extensive literature finding

00:49:50.220 --> 00:49:54.820
that the feelings that one has
after a breakup are very much

00:49:54.820 --> 00:49:57.360
like a clinical depression in many cases.

00:49:57.360 --> 00:49:59.840
But there are individuals
that can look at a breakup

00:49:59.840 --> 00:50:03.330
as a transient event
that they don't interpret

00:50:03.330 --> 00:50:07.050
as going to mean so much for
all aspects of their life

00:50:07.050 --> 00:50:10.240
or reshaping their view
of themselves, why?

00:50:10.240 --> 00:50:14.160
Well, we have different
levels of autonomic function.

00:50:14.160 --> 00:50:17.800
And depending on where our
seesaw is, if you will,

00:50:17.800 --> 00:50:21.350
some of us become extremely
distraught and can't recalibrate

00:50:21.350 --> 00:50:25.390
ourselves, can't adjust ourselves
down from stress to calm,

00:50:25.390 --> 00:50:28.740
or can't take ourselves
from exhausted to more alert

00:50:28.740 --> 00:50:30.460
if we need to do that on our own.

00:50:30.460 --> 00:50:32.840
And so that's why tools
for doing that exist.

00:50:32.840 --> 00:50:37.210
But attachment itself is about

00:50:37.210 --> 00:50:39.730
where our autonomic
nervous system resides.

00:50:39.730 --> 00:50:42.810
So if I were to offer a set
of tools around these topics

00:50:42.810 --> 00:50:45.550
of desire, love and attachment,
I would say, first of all,

00:50:45.550 --> 00:50:47.150
you might want to think
about whether or not you fall

00:50:47.150 --> 00:50:51.380
into the secure, insecure,
or other attachment styles.

00:50:51.380 --> 00:50:55.380
Second, I think it is vitally
important for all of us,

00:50:55.380 --> 00:50:58.000
but certainly for people
that are in relationships

00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:01.890
or seeking relationships to
be able to at least have some

00:51:01.890 --> 00:51:05.850
recognition of where our
autonomic nervous system tends

00:51:05.850 --> 00:51:08.940
to reside both in terms of
when we are with somebody

00:51:08.940 --> 00:51:10.430
and when they leave.

00:51:10.430 --> 00:51:12.350
When we are apart for
long periods of time,

00:51:12.350 --> 00:51:14.900
can we calm ourselves? Can we self-soothe?

00:51:14.900 --> 00:51:17.990
Or are we very much dependent
on the presence of another

00:51:17.990 --> 00:51:19.510
in order to feel soothed?

00:51:19.510 --> 00:51:21.960
Now, I absolutely want to emphasize

00:51:21.960 --> 00:51:23.390
that there is nothing wrong.

00:51:23.390 --> 00:51:26.180
In fact, there's everything
right with feeling great

00:51:26.180 --> 00:51:27.580
in the presence of somebody else.

00:51:27.580 --> 00:51:28.893
That is actually a hallmark

00:51:28.893 --> 00:51:32.100
of strong and quality attachments.

00:51:32.100 --> 00:51:34.900
These days, we hear the
term codependent a lot.

00:51:34.900 --> 00:51:37.190
This was a, I believe,
the term was first coined

00:51:37.190 --> 00:51:38.260
by Pia Mellody.

00:51:38.260 --> 00:51:42.980
And it actually does occupy
an important role in the world

00:51:42.980 --> 00:51:46.030
of trauma, trauma healing,
so-called trauma bonding,

00:51:46.030 --> 00:51:47.210
topics of another episode.

00:51:47.210 --> 00:51:48.920
Actually, did an episode
on fear and trauma.

00:51:48.920 --> 00:51:50.670
And we will do one all
about trauma bonding

00:51:50.670 --> 00:51:52.940
with an expert at some
point in the future.

00:51:52.940 --> 00:51:57.940
But codependence and codependency,
the term can sometimes

00:51:58.060 --> 00:52:03.060
be misinterpreted as any
dependence on another isn't good.

00:52:03.550 --> 00:52:05.970
Interdependence, a
healthy interdependence,

00:52:05.970 --> 00:52:07.090
of course is good.

00:52:07.090 --> 00:52:09.750
It is the hallmark of healthy
child-parent relations,

00:52:09.750 --> 00:52:12.530
sibling relations and romantic relations.

00:52:12.530 --> 00:52:16.510
But a key element of healthy
interdependence is that,

00:52:16.510 --> 00:52:19.210
yes, our autonomic
nervous system is adjusted

00:52:19.210 --> 00:52:22.500
by the presence of another, but
that also that we can adjust

00:52:22.500 --> 00:52:24.060
our own autonomic nervous system,

00:52:24.060 --> 00:52:26.410
even in the absence of that person.

00:52:26.410 --> 00:52:30.170
That if the person goes away
temporarily or permanently,

00:52:30.170 --> 00:52:33.630
that we can still regulate our
own autonomic nervous system,

00:52:33.630 --> 00:52:35.950
both from states of
stress to states of calm,

00:52:35.950 --> 00:52:40.350
both from states of exhaustion
to states of more alertness.

00:52:40.350 --> 00:52:41.660
And of course, we all need sleep

00:52:41.660 --> 00:52:43.850
to go from exhaustion to alertness.

00:52:43.850 --> 00:52:46.880
But what I'm referring to here
is the ability to regulate

00:52:46.880 --> 00:52:51.540
when distraught, or
regulate when fatigued,

00:52:51.540 --> 00:52:52.870
or feeling depressed.

00:52:52.870 --> 00:52:57.030
And that is and is all about
the autonomic nervous system.

00:52:57.030 --> 00:52:58.720
So as we talk about attachment styles,

00:52:58.720 --> 00:53:00.910
and we talk about infant and toddler

00:53:00.910 --> 00:53:01.843
and adult attachment styles,

00:53:01.843 --> 00:53:04.790
what we are really talking
about is a complex set

00:53:04.790 --> 00:53:05.800
of neural circuitries.

00:53:05.800 --> 00:53:08.610
And one of those neural
circuitries, which is absolutely

00:53:08.610 --> 00:53:11.070
crucial is this autonomic nervous system.

00:53:11.070 --> 00:53:14.820
So if the autonomic nervous
system is one key component

00:53:14.820 --> 00:53:18.880
of desire, love and attachment,
what are the other two?

00:53:18.880 --> 00:53:22.640
And what I'm going to tell you
next is largely the pioneering

00:53:22.640 --> 00:53:26.690
work of Helen Fisher, who
is really an anthropologist,

00:53:26.690 --> 00:53:29.650
who's become a bit of a
neuroscientist and has collaborated

00:53:29.650 --> 00:53:32.720
with neuroscientists to
establish brain areas

00:53:32.720 --> 00:53:34.330
and neural circuits that are associated

00:53:34.330 --> 00:53:37.020
with different aspects of
attachment, love and desire.

00:53:37.020 --> 00:53:39.690
I think the first really
high quality study

00:53:39.690 --> 00:53:42.740
of neural circuits
associated with these themes

00:53:42.740 --> 00:53:47.510
was a paper published in 2005
in a very fine anatomical

00:53:47.510 --> 00:53:50.470
journal, perhaps the best
neural anatomical journal,

00:53:50.470 --> 00:53:53.240
which is the Journal of
Comparative Neurology.

00:53:53.240 --> 00:53:55.240
The Journal of Comparative
Neurology has been around

00:53:55.240 --> 00:53:59.340
for more than 100 years and
is considered the archival

00:53:59.340 --> 00:54:02.790
location for placing really
high quality anatomy.

00:54:02.790 --> 00:54:04.610
They have tremendously high standards.

00:54:04.610 --> 00:54:07.277
And the study that I'm
referring to is entitled,

00:54:07.277 --> 00:54:09.500
"Romantic Love: An fMRI,"

00:54:09.500 --> 00:54:11.867
meaning functional
magnetic resonance imaging,

00:54:11.867 --> 00:54:14.900
"Study of a Neural
Mechanism for Mate Choice."

00:54:14.900 --> 00:54:19.130
And Dr. Fisher is a author on this paper

00:54:19.130 --> 00:54:21.990
as is Arthur Aron, and Lucy Brown.

00:54:21.990 --> 00:54:24.010
So all very fine researchers.

00:54:24.010 --> 00:54:27.580
And this study as well
as several other studies

00:54:27.580 --> 00:54:30.680
using magnetic resonance imaging,

00:54:30.680 --> 00:54:33.760
things like EEG, neuro
anatomical tracing, et cetera,

00:54:33.760 --> 00:54:35.690
have identified a large
number of brain areas

00:54:35.690 --> 00:54:37.140
that are associated with different aspects

00:54:37.140 --> 00:54:38.254
of desire, love, and attachment.

00:54:38.254 --> 00:54:40.670
And I'll just throw out a few
names of those brain areas

00:54:40.670 --> 00:54:41.630
and what they control.

00:54:41.630 --> 00:54:43.900
And then I'll tell you how those anchor

00:54:43.900 --> 00:54:46.430
to the other two categories
of neural circuits

00:54:46.430 --> 00:54:48.570
essential for desire,
love, and attachment.

00:54:48.570 --> 00:54:53.380
So not surprisingly the
dopamine system in the brain

00:54:53.380 --> 00:54:55.920
is associated with desire,
love, and attachment,

00:54:55.920 --> 00:54:58.760
and mainly with desire,
although to some extent, love.

00:54:58.760 --> 00:55:00.470
Dopamine is a neurochemical sometimes

00:55:00.470 --> 00:55:01.669
associated with reward.

00:55:01.669 --> 00:55:05.160
But as some of you have
heard me say before,

00:55:05.160 --> 00:55:09.660
it is mainly a molecule of
motivation, craving and pursuit.

00:55:09.660 --> 00:55:12.480
And that motivation, craving
and pursuit that relates

00:55:12.480 --> 00:55:15.950
to dopamine is not unique to
attachment, or love, or sex,

00:55:15.950 --> 00:55:17.070
or mating, et cetera.

00:55:17.070 --> 00:55:20.870
It is a universal generic
currency in the brain

00:55:20.870 --> 00:55:22.340
for pursuing something.

00:55:22.340 --> 00:55:25.350
Food when you're hungry,
a mate when you want one,

00:55:25.350 --> 00:55:29.010
to mate when you want to,
warmth when you're cold,

00:55:29.010 --> 00:55:30.260
et cetera, et cetera, okay?

00:55:30.260 --> 00:55:31.602
So it's not for one specific purpose.

00:55:31.602 --> 00:55:36.010
But the brain areas associated
with dopamine involve,

00:55:36.010 --> 00:55:38.570
for instance, the ventral tegmental area,

00:55:38.570 --> 00:55:42.910
the substantia nigra, areas of
that sort, the basal ganglia.

00:55:42.910 --> 00:55:44.060
You don't need to know these names,

00:55:44.060 --> 00:55:46.580
just understand that these
are networks of neurons

00:55:46.580 --> 00:55:49.950
that tend to have put the
person, you into a state

00:55:49.950 --> 00:55:54.010
of forward action and pursuit
and craving and motivation.

00:55:54.010 --> 00:55:57.180
They are not about being
quiescent, relaxed, et cetera.

00:55:57.180 --> 00:56:01.780
The neural circuits for
quiescence and relaxation

00:56:01.780 --> 00:56:04.760
are most associated with
love and attachment,

00:56:04.760 --> 00:56:07.170
not surprisingly, and
they're the neurochemical

00:56:07.170 --> 00:56:09.830
serotonin, and to some extent, oxytocin

00:56:09.830 --> 00:56:12.310
are the predominant
neurochemicals involved.

00:56:12.310 --> 00:56:13.538
And those are released from brain areas,

00:56:13.538 --> 00:56:16.510
such as the raphe nucleus
in the back of the brain.

00:56:16.510 --> 00:56:18.710
You may have heard that
the majority of serotonin

00:56:18.710 --> 00:56:22.110
in your body is made in your
gut, and indeed, that's true,

00:56:22.110 --> 00:56:25.640
but I hate to break it to
you, the serotonin in your gut

00:56:25.640 --> 00:56:28.790
is not responsible for your
feelings of love and attachment,

00:56:28.790 --> 00:56:30.150
at least not to a high degree.

00:56:30.150 --> 00:56:32.810
That's mainly going to be
the reflection of neurons

00:56:32.810 --> 00:56:35.160
in your brain that make serotonin.

00:56:35.160 --> 00:56:37.700
And there are other areas of
the brain that make serotonin

00:56:37.700 --> 00:56:39.990
as well and oxytocin as well,

00:56:39.990 --> 00:56:43.220
but they tend to be associated
with the warmth and calm,

00:56:43.220 --> 00:56:46.580
and the soothing that we feel
in the presence of another.

00:56:46.580 --> 00:56:49.950
And again, these are not
strictly divided circuits.

00:56:49.950 --> 00:56:52.087
We can have dopamine and
serotonin present in our brain

00:56:52.087 --> 00:56:56.050
and body at the same time to
equal or different degrees.

00:56:56.050 --> 00:56:59.070
And we return in a little bit
to what happens when levels

00:56:59.070 --> 00:57:01.590
of dopamine are very high and
levels of serotonin are low

00:57:01.590 --> 00:57:02.842
and vice versa and so on,

00:57:02.842 --> 00:57:07.842
including in states of
neurochemically modified states,

00:57:08.380 --> 00:57:11.690
as it were in, when we talk
about things like MDMA,

00:57:11.690 --> 00:57:13.480
so-called ecstasy.

00:57:13.480 --> 00:57:16.950
But in the meantime,
I want to just discuss

00:57:16.950 --> 00:57:20.530
the two neural circuits that use dopamine,

00:57:20.530 --> 00:57:22.780
that use serotonin and oxytocin,

00:57:22.780 --> 00:57:26.130
and that collaborate with
the autonomic nervous system

00:57:26.130 --> 00:57:29.350
to drive what we call
desire, love and attachment.

00:57:29.350 --> 00:57:33.770
And the three circuits are
autonomic nervous system,

00:57:33.770 --> 00:57:34.947
we talked about that one.

00:57:34.947 --> 00:57:37.920
Then there's the nervous system components

00:57:37.920 --> 00:57:42.400
or the neural circuits for
empathy, for being able to see

00:57:42.400 --> 00:57:46.740
and respond to indeed
match the emotional tone

00:57:46.740 --> 00:57:49.500
or the autonomic tone of another.

00:57:49.500 --> 00:57:51.230
And then there's the third category,

00:57:51.230 --> 00:57:52.350
and this might surprise some of you,

00:57:52.350 --> 00:57:53.800
it certainly surprised me,

00:57:53.800 --> 00:57:56.890
but the data point to the fact
that the third neural circuit

00:57:56.890 --> 00:57:59.860
that's very important
for establishing bonds

00:57:59.860 --> 00:58:02.780
is one associated with positive delusions.

00:58:02.780 --> 00:58:04.092
So given that the neural
circuits for empathy

00:58:04.092 --> 00:58:07.480
are absolutely crucial for falling in love

00:58:07.480 --> 00:58:10.330
and maintaining stable attachments,

00:58:10.330 --> 00:58:11.407
I'd like to talk about
those neural circuits

00:58:11.407 --> 00:58:13.290
and what they are.

00:58:13.290 --> 00:58:15.610
Now, often when we hear empathy, we think,

00:58:15.610 --> 00:58:19.750
oh, empathy is really about
listening to and really

00:58:19.750 --> 00:58:21.630
understanding what
somebody else is feeling.

00:58:21.630 --> 00:58:23.970
Maybe even feeling what they're feeling.

00:58:23.970 --> 00:58:27.130
And indeed that's the case,
but what do we mean by that?

00:58:27.130 --> 00:58:29.850
Right? What is it to
feel what another feels?

00:58:29.850 --> 00:58:33.180
Well, what it means is that their seesaw

00:58:33.180 --> 00:58:36.040
is driving your seesaw,

00:58:36.040 --> 00:58:39.720
or your seesaw is somehow
driving their seesaw.

00:58:39.720 --> 00:58:42.650
That there's a match in terms
of the tilt of those seesaws.

00:58:42.650 --> 00:58:44.650
Now it doesn't have to
be an exact match, right?

00:58:44.650 --> 00:58:45.695
If someone that you really he care about

00:58:45.695 --> 00:58:50.340
is very, very stressed, you
could also become very stressed.

00:58:50.340 --> 00:58:52.930
That's a form of empathic matching,

00:58:52.930 --> 00:58:54.740
and there are indeed
neural circuits for that.

00:58:54.740 --> 00:58:57.210
I'll describe what those neural
circuits are in a moment.

00:58:57.210 --> 00:59:00.470
But sometimes the best role
for us to take is actually one

00:59:00.470 --> 00:59:03.860
in which we are calm when
the person that we care about

00:59:03.860 --> 00:59:05.260
or that we are romantically involved

00:59:05.260 --> 00:59:07.080
with is very, very anxious.

00:59:07.080 --> 00:59:10.260
And in a few minutes, I'll
talk about how matching

00:59:10.260 --> 00:59:13.080
of emotional tone can be good or bad

00:59:13.080 --> 00:59:14.880
for the stability of a relationship,

00:59:16.210 --> 00:59:19.930
and complementarity of autonomic matching

00:59:19.930 --> 00:59:21.370
can be good or bad.

00:59:21.370 --> 00:59:25.350
In other words, sometimes it's
beneficial for a relationship

00:59:25.350 --> 00:59:27.960
to go into the same state as the other.

00:59:27.960 --> 00:59:30.810
And sometimes it's more
beneficial for us to not go

00:59:30.810 --> 00:59:33.700
into the same state as the other.

00:59:33.700 --> 00:59:37.470
But the important feature here
is that when we talk about

00:59:37.470 --> 00:59:40.330
emotional matching or empathy
or going into the same state

00:59:40.330 --> 00:59:42.680
or not going into the same
state, what we are really talking

00:59:42.680 --> 00:59:47.500
about is whether or not
the autonomic seesaw

00:59:47.500 --> 00:59:50.410
of one individual is
driving the autonomic seesaw

00:59:50.410 --> 00:59:52.210
of the other individual.

00:59:52.210 --> 00:59:56.520
And this is a vital principle
for how we fall in love

00:59:56.520 --> 00:59:57.560
and form attachments.

00:59:57.560 --> 00:59:59.440
And it's actually part of the desire

00:59:59.440 --> 01:00:01.187
and mating process itself.

01:00:02.690 --> 01:00:07.690
I would go so far as to say
that one of the prerequisites

01:00:07.780 --> 01:00:11.890
to the propagation and
expansion of our species

01:00:11.890 --> 01:00:15.480
is this notion of autonomic regulation.

01:00:15.480 --> 01:00:18.760
And to some extent, matching
of autonomic nervous systems.

01:00:18.760 --> 01:00:20.930
Let me explain what I mean.

01:00:20.930 --> 01:00:24.700
Last I checked, the only way
that new humans can be created

01:00:24.700 --> 01:00:29.700
is by way of sperm meeting
egg, either in body or in dish,

01:00:29.840 --> 01:00:33.980
but sperm meets egg and then
typically nine months later,

01:00:33.980 --> 01:00:35.113
we have a human baby.

01:00:36.510 --> 01:00:40.540
The process of bringing
sperm to egg, right?

01:00:40.540 --> 01:00:43.100
Mating behavior, sex behavior in humans

01:00:43.100 --> 01:00:46.690
is one of autonomic regulation.

01:00:46.690 --> 01:00:51.690
And what I mean by that is
the process of finding a mate,

01:00:54.180 --> 01:00:56.150
and in this case, I mean,
actually someone to mate with,

01:00:56.150 --> 01:00:59.080
typically, well,
scenarios vary, typically,

01:00:59.080 --> 01:01:03.120
is one of elevated autonomic arousal,

01:01:03.120 --> 01:01:04.920
meaning increased activation

01:01:04.920 --> 01:01:07.090
of the so-called
sympathetic nervous system.

01:01:07.090 --> 01:01:09.170
This is related to dopamine release

01:01:09.170 --> 01:01:11.360
and it's related to epinephrine release.

01:01:11.360 --> 01:01:15.030
There has to be a pursuit
or at least there has to be

01:01:15.030 --> 01:01:18.360
a mobilization to arrive
in the same location

01:01:18.360 --> 01:01:20.380
whereby one can mate, right?

01:01:20.380 --> 01:01:22.523
That almost always is the case.

01:01:23.680 --> 01:01:27.860
However, the sexual arousal itself

01:01:29.240 --> 01:01:31.830
in both males and females

01:01:31.830 --> 01:01:36.830
is actually driven primarily
by the parasympathetic arm

01:01:36.900 --> 01:01:39.010
of the autonomic nervous system.

01:01:39.010 --> 01:01:44.010
So while pursuit is one of
alertness and sympathetic drive,

01:01:44.180 --> 01:01:47.100
as we say, again, sympathy is not really

01:01:47.100 --> 01:01:48.450
what's at play here,

01:01:48.450 --> 01:01:50.020
the word simple means together,

01:01:50.020 --> 01:01:52.530
and the activation of the
autonomic nervous system

01:01:52.530 --> 01:01:53.820
toward more alert state

01:01:53.820 --> 01:01:55.343
is because of a
sympathetic nervous system,

01:01:55.343 --> 01:01:58.550
meaning the co-activation
together of many neurons

01:01:58.550 --> 01:02:00.360
in the brain and spinal cord.

01:02:00.360 --> 01:02:04.147
But then the actual
physiological arousal state

01:02:04.147 --> 01:02:07.082
