that a relationship will last.

01:15:41.560 --> 01:15:43.080
And those are many,

01:15:43.080 --> 01:15:46.460
but mainly fall under this
category of positive delusions.

01:15:46.460 --> 01:15:48.980
I'll return to those in what
those exactly look like.

01:15:48.980 --> 01:15:52.900
But there are also just a
handful of things that predict

01:15:52.900 --> 01:15:55.350
that a relationship will fail over time.

01:15:55.350 --> 01:15:58.210
This is largely the work of the Gottman's,

01:15:58.210 --> 01:15:59.790
is actually a husband and wife team

01:15:59.790 --> 01:16:03.250
up at the University of
Washington in Seattle.

01:16:03.250 --> 01:16:06.240
The Gottman's have, run a laboratory

01:16:06.240 --> 01:16:08.050
in the department of
psychology for a long time.

01:16:08.050 --> 01:16:09.670
They've also done a lot of public facing

01:16:09.670 --> 01:16:11.620
work around relationships.

01:16:11.620 --> 01:16:15.630
And they've talked about
the various aspects

01:16:15.630 --> 01:16:17.910
of relationships and
interactions between people

01:16:17.910 --> 01:16:20.310
that predict either staying
together or breaking up.

01:16:20.310 --> 01:16:24.080
So much so that they've
established a method

01:16:24.080 --> 01:16:27.950
by which they can look at video
interactions between couples

01:16:27.950 --> 01:16:30.980
and with very high degree
of certainty predict

01:16:30.980 --> 01:16:32.720
whether or not those
couples will stay together

01:16:32.720 --> 01:16:34.020
or break up over time.

01:16:34.020 --> 01:16:35.510
And they've identified what they call

01:16:35.510 --> 01:16:37.950
the four horsemen of relationships.

01:16:37.950 --> 01:16:40.581
These are things that essentially,

01:16:40.581 --> 01:16:45.180
almost always predict that
a couple will break up.

01:16:45.180 --> 01:16:49.470
And I think the current
number on this is that Gottman

01:16:49.470 --> 01:16:53.110
can predict divorce with 94% accuracy,

01:16:53.110 --> 01:16:55.140
which if you think about
is pretty remarkable.

01:16:55.140 --> 01:16:57.940
So even though these are
purely psychological studies,

01:16:57.940 --> 01:17:01.530
I'm not aware of any analysis
of underlying physiology,

01:17:01.530 --> 01:17:05.320
there are some things that they
can observe between couples

01:17:05.320 --> 01:17:08.020
that can lead them to predict
whether or not a couple

01:17:08.020 --> 01:17:11.420
will stay together or
break up with 94% accuracy.

01:17:11.420 --> 01:17:12.800
So what are those things?

01:17:12.800 --> 01:17:15.370
Those four behaviors, what
they call the Four Horsemen

01:17:15.370 --> 01:17:18.690
of the Apocalypse
[laughs] for relationships

01:17:19.791 --> 01:17:24.791
are one, criticism, two,
defensiveness, three, stonewalling,

01:17:25.920 --> 01:17:30.570
and four, contempt, with
contempt being the most powerful

01:17:30.570 --> 01:17:34.100
predictor of breaking up.

01:17:34.100 --> 01:17:38.450
Criticism, of course, does
not mean that there's no place

01:17:38.450 --> 01:17:40.920
for criticism in stable relationships.

01:17:40.920 --> 01:17:42.370
Of course, there is.

01:17:42.370 --> 01:17:44.670
Has to do with how
frequent and how intensely

01:17:44.670 --> 01:17:46.150
that criticism is voiced.

01:17:46.150 --> 01:17:49.400
Defensiveness, of
course, is defensiveness.

01:17:49.400 --> 01:17:54.280
We know as the lack of
ability to hear another

01:17:54.280 --> 01:17:55.560
or to adopt their stance.

01:17:55.560 --> 01:17:57.020
So lack of empathy,

01:17:57.020 --> 01:18:00.430
I think is one way to
interpret defensiveness.

01:18:00.430 --> 01:18:03.260
Stonewalling, which is
actually another form

01:18:03.260 --> 01:18:04.140
of lack of empathy.

01:18:04.140 --> 01:18:06.220
It's a turning off of this neural circuit

01:18:06.220 --> 01:18:09.230
that's so critical for
desire, love and attachment.

01:18:09.230 --> 01:18:13.610
The stonewalling essentially
means the emotional response

01:18:13.610 --> 01:18:15.540
or the request of another
is completely cut off.

01:18:15.540 --> 01:18:18.840
So it's, I don't think there's
been brain imaging of this,

01:18:18.840 --> 01:18:21.725
but I think, we can reasonably
imagine that it involves

01:18:21.725 --> 01:18:25.960
untethering your insular
response from the other

01:18:25.960 --> 01:18:26.950
and what they're dealing with,

01:18:26.950 --> 01:18:29.764
and focusing your insular response,

01:18:29.764 --> 01:18:33.310
[giggles] no pun intended,
on your own internal state

01:18:33.310 --> 01:18:36.020
or perhaps the state of
someone else entirely.

01:18:36.020 --> 01:18:37.430
I'll talk about infidelity in a moment.

01:18:37.430 --> 01:18:38.600
And then contempt.

01:18:38.600 --> 01:18:40.149
And contempt has actually been referred

01:18:40.149 --> 01:18:43.300
to as the sulfuric acid of relationship.

01:18:43.300 --> 01:18:45.870
I didn't say that, but
Gottman and colleagues have.

01:18:45.870 --> 01:18:48.480
That it is such a powerful predictor

01:18:48.480 --> 01:18:51.810
of divorce and breakups in the future.

01:18:51.810 --> 01:18:55.350
And contempt, of course, by
definition is the feeling

01:18:55.350 --> 01:18:57.870
that a person or thing
is beneath consideration,

01:18:57.870 --> 01:19:00.850
worthlessness or deserving scorn.

01:19:00.850 --> 01:19:03.520
And apparently they can
identify this in the videos

01:19:03.520 --> 01:19:06.170
of couples having
discussions and interacting

01:19:06.170 --> 01:19:11.170
by very elaborate eye rolls,
by expressions of anger

01:19:11.790 --> 01:19:14.750
in one individual when their
partner is actually expressing

01:19:14.750 --> 01:19:16.990
enthusiasm or excitement about something.

01:19:16.990 --> 01:19:20.040
It's the, oh yeah, you would say that,

01:19:20.040 --> 01:19:23.500
or deep seated resentment
toward the other,

01:19:23.500 --> 01:19:28.280
so much so that it's apparent
that one actively dislikes

01:19:28.280 --> 01:19:29.253
the other partner.

01:19:30.370 --> 01:19:33.990
So contempt, disregard for
something that should be taken

01:19:33.990 --> 01:19:36.210
into account is the other
way to think about it.

01:19:36.210 --> 01:19:39.440
That runs counter to all
of the neural circuits,

01:19:39.440 --> 01:19:40.730
all three of the neural circuits

01:19:40.730 --> 01:19:41.750
that we talked about before.

01:19:41.750 --> 01:19:45.340
It certainly, it is the
antithesis of empathy.

01:19:45.340 --> 01:19:47.550
It is anything but a positive delusion.

01:19:47.550 --> 01:19:49.550
It's really looking at
the other individual,

01:19:49.550 --> 01:19:51.490
either accurately or inaccurately

01:19:51.490 --> 01:19:54.030
as somebody that you despise.

01:19:54.030 --> 01:19:58.390
And then it is an absolute
inversion of the autonomic

01:19:58.390 --> 01:20:00.840
seesaw matching that I
was talking about before.

01:20:00.840 --> 01:20:03.610
It's a dissociating of your
seesaw from their seesaw.

01:20:03.610 --> 01:20:05.150
They're very excited about something,

01:20:05.150 --> 01:20:06.940
you're unexcited by it.

01:20:06.940 --> 01:20:09.160
In fact, it's an inversion of their seesaw

01:20:09.160 --> 01:20:11.893
where they're excited, you're down.

01:20:12.750 --> 01:20:14.930
They're down, you are up, okay?

01:20:14.930 --> 01:20:19.640
So it's basically an inversion
of all of the neural circuits

01:20:19.640 --> 01:20:22.740
that Helen Fisher and others
have identified as critical

01:20:22.740 --> 01:20:24.330
for desire, love, and attachment.

01:20:24.330 --> 01:20:28.300
And therefore it's not
surprising that it is so strongly

01:20:28.300 --> 01:20:29.510
predictive of breakups,

01:20:29.510 --> 01:20:32.130
and in the case of married
couples, of divorce.

01:20:32.130 --> 01:20:33.541
For those of you that are
interested in the work

01:20:33.541 --> 01:20:37.040
of the Gottman's and similar work,

01:20:37.040 --> 01:20:39.220
they've written several popular books.

01:20:39.220 --> 01:20:40.860
They're fairly easy to find.

01:20:40.860 --> 01:20:44.020
We can link to one of
those in the caption.

01:20:44.020 --> 01:20:45.010
But they've also developed

01:20:45.010 --> 01:20:48.500
some quite interesting online resources

01:20:48.500 --> 01:20:50.500
in their so-called Love Lab.

01:20:50.500 --> 01:20:53.590
I guess it's fortunate that
they didn't call it the Hate Lab

01:20:53.590 --> 01:20:54.430
or the Breakup Lab,

01:20:54.430 --> 01:20:56.940
'cause they focused a lot
on what predicts breakups.

01:20:56.940 --> 01:21:00.320
But they've also written
extensively and researched

01:21:00.320 --> 01:21:02.550
extensively in peer-reviewed studies

01:21:03.610 --> 01:21:08.190
what makes people find
appropriate partners for them,

01:21:08.190 --> 01:21:12.470
and to maintain those
partnerships over time.

01:21:12.470 --> 01:21:15.080
So you can go, you can
search for Love Lab,

01:21:15.080 --> 01:21:17.100
University of Washington, Gottman,

01:21:17.100 --> 01:21:19.370
or any number of their various books.

01:21:19.370 --> 01:21:22.163
I think you'll find some
useful resources there.

01:21:24.170 --> 01:21:27.173
I want to shift back to
the work of Helen Fisher.

01:21:28.140 --> 01:21:31.150
She's made some very
interesting statements

01:21:31.150 --> 01:21:33.330
and some very interesting observations

01:21:33.330 --> 01:21:35.840
that at least to my mind map very well

01:21:35.840 --> 01:21:39.470
onto the knowledge of neural
circuitry both in humans

01:21:39.470 --> 01:21:41.630
and in non-human primates
and in other species.

01:21:41.630 --> 01:21:44.683
I realize that she's the
only name in the game.

01:21:45.930 --> 01:21:49.800
But she's made some observations
that I think are very,

01:21:49.800 --> 01:21:52.620
as we say, parsimonious, meaning
they allow us to organize

01:21:52.620 --> 01:21:55.710
a lot of this stuff into
some distinct frameworks.

01:21:55.710 --> 01:21:58.472
Now, she's also done some
really beautiful studies

01:21:58.472 --> 01:22:02.320
that involve data from millions
or even tens of millions

01:22:02.320 --> 01:22:04.020
of individuals on dating sites.

01:22:04.020 --> 01:22:05.340
So I'm going to share
those with you in a moment.

01:22:05.340 --> 01:22:10.340
But before I do that, I just
want to paraphrase Dr. Fisher,

01:22:11.650 --> 01:22:16.650
who said that sex drive
or desire that the pursuit

01:22:16.810 --> 01:22:19.920
of someone to mate with,
meaning to mate, the verb,

01:22:19.920 --> 01:22:24.920
not necessarily to find a mate, may be,

01:22:25.370 --> 01:22:28.010
she didn't say definitively,
but may be a way to forage

01:22:28.010 --> 01:22:31.570
for potential love partners
that the arc of this

01:22:31.570 --> 01:22:34.580
whole business is really the
order that we're describing it,

01:22:34.580 --> 01:22:39.410
that it's desire, then
love, and then attachment.

01:22:39.410 --> 01:22:43.120
And that oftentimes
people can get confused.

01:22:43.120 --> 01:22:44.670
You may know some of these people,

01:22:44.670 --> 01:22:48.400
you may be one of these individuals
who might confuse desire

01:22:48.400 --> 01:22:53.400
for attachment or might
confuse love for attachment,

01:22:53.830 --> 01:22:56.780
but that there's a sequence of recruitment

01:22:56.780 --> 01:22:59.640
of these neural circuits
that's established first

01:22:59.640 --> 01:23:02.440
from the pursuit of someone to mate with.

01:23:02.440 --> 01:23:06.830
And she's placed us in the
context of more modern dating

01:23:06.830 --> 01:23:11.040
themes where depending on
culture, people might explore

01:23:12.640 --> 01:23:15.990
several, maybe many,
many individuals before,

01:23:15.990 --> 01:23:18.770
quote, unquote, settling
down with somebody,

01:23:18.770 --> 01:23:21.100
at least for some period of time.

01:23:21.100 --> 01:23:23.480
I think that's an interesting framework

01:23:23.480 --> 01:23:28.480
because it circumvents a lot
of the, frankly, unanswerable

01:23:28.650 --> 01:23:32.330
questions about whether
or not humans were meant

01:23:32.330 --> 01:23:34.220
to be monogamous or whether
or not they weren't.

01:23:34.220 --> 01:23:37.110
Those are conversations
that hold cultural context,

01:23:37.110 --> 01:23:39.770
that hold all sorts of context,

01:23:39.770 --> 01:23:42.750
that really can't be addressed
in a laboratory setting.

01:23:42.750 --> 01:23:46.760
But this idea that sex
drive is a way to forage

01:23:46.760 --> 01:23:51.300
for potential love partners
and that love is a litmus test

01:23:51.300 --> 01:23:54.640
for whether or not longer
term or deeper attachments

01:23:54.640 --> 01:23:58.380
can and will form, is one that
at least makes sense to me.

01:23:58.380 --> 01:24:00.446
Later in the episode, we'll
talk about this notion

01:24:00.446 --> 01:24:02.770
of sex drive and desire.

01:24:02.770 --> 01:24:06.950
I'll actually talk about some
tools that have very strong

01:24:06.950 --> 01:24:10.360
data really to support them
in terms of things that people

01:24:10.360 --> 01:24:13.483
can do or take to increase
libido, both men and women,

01:24:14.570 --> 01:24:17.350
because there's actually
quite good data on that now.

01:24:17.350 --> 01:24:20.490
But in the meantime, I want
to talk about some of the work

01:24:20.490 --> 01:24:22.330
that Dr. Fisher has done in terms

01:24:22.330 --> 01:24:25.260
of categorizing people into...

01:24:25.260 --> 01:24:27.160
Again, we have four groups.

01:24:27.160 --> 01:24:30.300
These are distinct from the A, B, C, and D

01:24:30.300 --> 01:24:32.220
attachment styles described earlier.

01:24:32.220 --> 01:24:33.660
Although as I describe them,

01:24:33.660 --> 01:24:36.400
you might be able to map
them somewhat onto those.

01:24:36.400 --> 01:24:41.400
And these four groups are
groups that were defined

01:24:41.510 --> 01:24:44.960
through her studies of
people that were, or are,

01:24:44.960 --> 01:24:49.600
I don't know if they were or
if they are still on match.com,

01:24:49.600 --> 01:24:51.640
but a very extensive dataset.

01:24:51.640 --> 01:24:55.160
So again, millions if not tens
of millions of individuals.

01:24:55.160 --> 01:24:56.670
The number I heard her quote,

01:24:56.670 --> 01:24:59.270
and forgive me if this is not accurate,

01:24:59.270 --> 01:25:02.713
is that in upwards of
40 million individuals,

01:25:04.370 --> 01:25:06.850
in terms of whether or
not their neurochemical

01:25:06.850 --> 01:25:08.810
and hormone systems are tuned

01:25:08.810 --> 01:25:11.023
toward particular types of behaviors.

01:25:12.400 --> 01:25:13.330
What do I mean by that?

01:25:13.330 --> 01:25:17.240
Well, both men and
women, males and females

01:25:17.240 --> 01:25:19.300
have both testosterone and estrogen.

01:25:19.300 --> 01:25:22.030
Typically, again, these
are averages, but typically

01:25:22.030 --> 01:25:24.680
men have more testosterone
than they do estrogen,

01:25:24.680 --> 01:25:26.920
and they have more
testosterone than do women,

01:25:26.920 --> 01:25:28.650
and less estrogen then do women.

01:25:28.650 --> 01:25:30.660
Typically women have more estrogen

01:25:30.660 --> 01:25:33.223
than they do testosterone,
again, averages.

01:25:34.320 --> 01:25:38.270
And they have less testosterone than men,

01:25:38.270 --> 01:25:40.900
more estrogen than men,
and so on and so forth.

01:25:40.900 --> 01:25:42.950
But both hormone systems are active

01:25:42.950 --> 01:25:46.450
in both sets of individuals.

01:25:46.450 --> 01:25:50.310
And of course, all
humans, as far as we know,

01:25:50.310 --> 01:25:53.080
manufacture both dopamine and serotonin.

01:25:53.080 --> 01:25:56.580
Dopamine, as I mentioned
earlier, has a number of effects

01:25:56.580 --> 01:25:57.413
in the brain and body.

01:25:57.413 --> 01:25:59.440
But one of the primary
effects is that it places us

01:25:59.440 --> 01:26:03.400
into states of motivation and
pursuit for various things.

01:26:03.400 --> 01:26:07.660
There is somewhat close
relationship between the dopamine

01:26:07.660 --> 01:26:11.800
system and the testosterone
system in the hypothalamus,

01:26:11.800 --> 01:26:13.360
this brain area above
the roof of your mouth.

01:26:13.360 --> 01:26:15.610
And the pituitary gland,
which is responsible

01:26:15.610 --> 01:26:20.223
for making hormones that make
the ovaries and or testes,

01:26:21.500 --> 01:26:23.194
secrete testosterone or estrogen.

01:26:23.194 --> 01:26:27.567
So there's a lot of signaling
that occurs such that dopamine

01:26:27.567 --> 01:26:31.660
and testosterone tend to
operate as close cousins

01:26:31.660 --> 01:26:33.400
in a system of pursuit.

01:26:33.400 --> 01:26:37.350
And conversely, the serotonin
system tends to on average

01:26:37.350 --> 01:26:41.250
collaborate with the estrogen
system to impart certain

01:26:41.250 --> 01:26:43.460
physiological functions and behaviors.

01:26:43.460 --> 01:26:48.410
So these aren't hard and fast,
or I guess better stated,

01:26:48.410 --> 01:26:51.450
these aren't strict black
and white categorizations,

01:26:51.450 --> 01:26:53.510
but I think those general themes hold

01:26:53.510 --> 01:26:56.520
when you look at the
animal and human data.

01:26:56.520 --> 01:27:01.520
So Dr. Fisher has taken some
liberties, but I think they are

01:27:01.990 --> 01:27:04.210
what I would call logically,
and scientifically,

01:27:04.210 --> 01:27:06.790
and neurobiologically grounded liberties

01:27:06.790 --> 01:27:10.570
in classifying individuals
who are on these dating sites

01:27:10.570 --> 01:27:13.010
according to the types
of things they report

01:27:13.010 --> 01:27:15.500
about themselves and the
type of people they tend

01:27:15.500 --> 01:27:19.110
to match with on these dating sites,

01:27:19.110 --> 01:27:21.163
and created these four categories.

01:27:22.620 --> 01:27:25.068
The four categories are, she calls one,

01:27:25.068 --> 01:27:27.770
the dopamine category.

01:27:27.770 --> 01:27:30.470
So these are people who
would have high dopamine.

01:27:30.470 --> 01:27:34.000
And again, that's just a name.

01:27:34.000 --> 01:27:36.810
It doesn't mean they
have low anything else,

01:27:36.810 --> 01:27:39.490
but they are high on the dopamine scale.

01:27:39.490 --> 01:27:43.440
People who rate high on the
dopamine scale tend to be

01:27:43.440 --> 01:27:45.190
what the scientists and psychologists call

01:27:45.190 --> 01:27:47.090
high sensation seeking, novel seeking.

01:27:47.090 --> 01:27:49.840
They like new things,
they like spontaneity,

01:27:49.840 --> 01:27:51.490
they tend to be very adventurous.

01:27:51.490 --> 01:27:52.940
And I think that's largely true.

01:27:52.940 --> 01:27:55.100
If you look at the conditions

01:27:55.100 --> 01:27:59.500
where dopamine is super physiological,

01:27:59.500 --> 01:28:02.710
it's elevated beyond abnormal levels.

01:28:02.710 --> 01:28:06.500
Things like mania or when
people take certain drugs

01:28:06.500 --> 01:28:08.690
of abuse, like cocaine or amphetamine

01:28:08.690 --> 01:28:12.550
that really raise dopamine
levels up very, very high.

01:28:12.550 --> 01:28:15.630
For some period of time,
they do tend to increase

01:28:15.630 --> 01:28:18.090
energy motivation and novelty seeking.

01:28:18.090 --> 01:28:20.100
And of course, drugs like
amphetamine and cocaine

01:28:20.100 --> 01:28:22.160
have all sorts of deleterious effects

01:28:22.160 --> 01:28:23.210
that I don't need to go into here,

01:28:23.210 --> 01:28:24.900
but it's worth pointing out.

01:28:24.900 --> 01:28:27.300
But they don't tend to make
people calm and relaxed

01:28:27.300 --> 01:28:30.730
and seek soothing interactions.

01:28:30.730 --> 01:28:34.160
Conversely, the group
that Dr. Fisher calls

01:28:34.160 --> 01:28:39.160
the serotonin group
tend to be more grounded

01:28:40.240 --> 01:28:43.430
in soothing activities,
quiescent type activities.

01:28:43.430 --> 01:28:45.610
They actually tend to be, on average,

01:28:45.610 --> 01:28:47.790
they tend to like rules and follow rules,

01:28:47.790 --> 01:28:50.220
they tend to be homebodies,
this sort of thing.

01:28:50.220 --> 01:28:53.690
They're really, you can
imagine them this stable types,

01:28:53.690 --> 01:28:55.010
but they really like stability.

01:28:55.010 --> 01:28:57.320
They're not really into
spontaneity as much,

01:28:57.320 --> 01:28:58.350
again, averages.

01:28:58.350 --> 01:29:01.420
And then she created two other categories,

01:29:01.420 --> 01:29:04.630
the testosterone category
of high testosterone.

01:29:04.630 --> 01:29:07.640
This again, could be males or females.

01:29:07.640 --> 01:29:10.810
And then the estrogen category,

01:29:10.810 --> 01:29:12.110
again, could be males or females.

01:29:12.110 --> 01:29:13.917
And she gave these different names

01:29:13.917 --> 01:29:15.730
that I won't go into here.

01:29:15.730 --> 01:29:17.020
You can look up her work online,

01:29:17.020 --> 01:29:20.480
but she names like the
director, and the follower,

01:29:20.480 --> 01:29:21.313
and things like that.

01:29:21.313 --> 01:29:23.040
But I don't really want to use
those as much as I want to stick

01:29:23.040 --> 01:29:24.660
to the biological terms.

01:29:24.660 --> 01:29:28.470
So we have dopamine, serotonin,
testosterone, and estrogen.

01:29:28.470 --> 01:29:32.757
Now that might seem like an
unfair overgeneralization,

01:29:33.640 --> 01:29:36.890
but what's interesting is
not necessarily the name

01:29:36.890 --> 01:29:38.650
or the neurochemical system, right?

01:29:38.650 --> 01:29:41.350
Those could have just been
called category one, two, three

01:29:41.350 --> 01:29:45.320
and four for all that matters here.

01:29:45.320 --> 01:29:49.560
What is interesting is seeing
how those different groups

01:29:49.560 --> 01:29:53.290
of individuals that she
absolutely can categorize

01:29:53.290 --> 01:29:57.120
based on their self-reported preferences

01:29:57.120 --> 01:29:59.960
about behaviors and certain
kinds of interactions.

01:29:59.960 --> 01:30:03.080
How those groups tend
to pair up with people

01:30:03.080 --> 01:30:05.410
in the same or opposite categories.

01:30:05.410 --> 01:30:08.510
So what her studies reveal
is that people that fall

01:30:08.510 --> 01:30:11.100
into the high sensation
seeking, novelty seeking,

01:30:11.100 --> 01:30:13.430
spontaneity category,
the one that she calls

01:30:13.430 --> 01:30:17.640
the high dopamine category
tend to pair up with, at least

01:30:17.640 --> 01:30:21.190
in the short term, tend
to pair up with people

01:30:21.190 --> 01:30:23.760
who are also in that
dopaminergic category.

01:30:23.760 --> 01:30:26.990
So these would be people
that would spontaneously

01:30:26.990 --> 01:30:30.030
take a trip or explore
something new or new restaurant.

01:30:30.030 --> 01:30:34.490
They tend to be creative
and explorative types.

01:30:34.490 --> 01:30:39.490
So that group on average
tends to date and mate,

01:30:40.010 --> 01:30:42.370
and potentially form long-term

01:30:42.370 --> 01:30:44.470
relationships within category.

01:30:44.470 --> 01:30:46.040
Again, averages.

01:30:46.040 --> 01:30:49.930
Individuals that she placed
into the serotonin group

01:30:49.930 --> 01:30:52.960
or what she hypothesized would
be a high serotonin group,

01:30:52.960 --> 01:30:54.388
again, they didn't measure serotonin,

01:30:54.388 --> 01:30:59.388
but people that tend to place
value on stability, on rules,

01:30:59.680 --> 01:31:03.840
on certain forms of
traditional organization

01:31:03.840 --> 01:31:05.590
at home and in relationships,

01:31:05.590 --> 01:31:10.580
those people also tended to
pair up with select date,

01:31:11.460 --> 01:31:14.720
we presume mate with and
form stable relationships

01:31:14.720 --> 01:31:17.280
with people in the same category.

01:31:17.280 --> 01:31:19.780
Now, individuals in the
other two categories,

01:31:19.780 --> 01:31:21.560
the high testosterone group,

01:31:21.560 --> 01:31:23.520
and again, testosterone wasn't measured,

01:31:23.520 --> 01:31:25.570
but she called it the
high testosterone group,

01:31:25.570 --> 01:31:30.570
but these are people that
tend to be very directive,

01:31:30.870 --> 01:31:33.330
they tend to know what they
want and are comfortable telling

01:31:33.330 --> 01:31:35.570
other people what they want.

01:31:35.570 --> 01:31:40.570
And from them, these are
individuals that in her studies

01:31:40.930 --> 01:31:44.240
and in other studies tend to
be a little bit challenging,

01:31:44.240 --> 01:31:47.230
meaning they not necessarily
challenging to be around,

01:31:47.230 --> 01:31:49.490
but they tend to challenge other people,

01:31:49.490 --> 01:31:52.770
push them in order to
expand their boundaries,

01:31:52.770 --> 01:31:55.890
either for sake of the
relationship or just in general.

01:31:55.890 --> 01:31:57.730
And the people they tend
to push are the people that

01:31:57.730 --> 01:31:59.810
they pair up with, which are the people

01:31:59.810 --> 01:32:02.340
in the estrogen category,
what she called high estrogen.

01:32:02.340 --> 01:32:03.840
Again, they didn't measure estrogen,

01:32:03.840 --> 01:32:07.630
but the people in the estrogen
category were the ones

01:32:07.630 --> 01:32:10.900
that described themselves
and their choices in life

01:32:10.900 --> 01:32:13.520
and their preferences as being nurturing.

01:32:13.520 --> 01:32:16.070
They actually seem to
like it when someone else

01:32:16.070 --> 01:32:19.800
is making the major
decisions, not every decision.

01:32:19.800 --> 01:32:22.160
They certainly like to
be heard, of course,

01:32:22.160 --> 01:32:23.470
in terms of their preferences.

01:32:23.470 --> 01:32:27.107
But that those two types, what
she called the testosterone

01:32:27.107 --> 01:32:29.830
and the estrogen type tend to pair up.

01:32:29.830 --> 01:32:31.357
So why are these categorizations

01:32:31.357 --> 01:32:33.630
and these averages interesting to me,

01:32:33.630 --> 01:32:36.300
at least interesting
enough to convey to you?

01:32:36.300 --> 01:32:38.940
The reason they're interesting to me is,

01:32:38.940 --> 01:32:40.490
again, not because of their names,

01:32:40.490 --> 01:32:43.270
these molecules were not
measured in these individuals,

01:32:43.270 --> 01:32:46.530
but that they once again
bring us to the themes

01:32:46.530 --> 01:32:48.170
that we addressed before,

01:32:48.170 --> 01:32:51.550
which are the autonomic nervous
system and whether or not

01:32:51.550 --> 01:32:54.900
it tends to be shifted more
towards alertness in action

01:32:54.900 --> 01:32:59.630
or more towards a stable
equilibrium or more towards calm,

01:32:59.630 --> 01:33:04.530
and whether or not individuals
are selecting for people

01:33:04.530 --> 01:33:07.430
who have autonomic nervous
systems that are more or less

01:33:07.430 --> 01:33:10.780
like theirs before they even meet, right?

01:33:10.780 --> 01:33:13.960
So again, going back
to this seesaw analogy,

01:33:13.960 --> 01:33:16.690
it's almost like people
who have the flat seesaw,

01:33:16.690 --> 01:33:19.650
alert but calm, but not extremely alert,

01:33:19.650 --> 01:33:24.650
not extremely overly calm in
situations but in the middle,

01:33:25.440 --> 01:33:27.670
seem to be seeking out
people that are also

01:33:27.670 --> 01:33:31.370
at that autonomic equilibrium.

01:33:31.370 --> 01:33:33.770
People in the, what she
called the dopamine category,

01:33:33.770 --> 01:33:35.120
which are really can just be described

01:33:35.120 --> 01:33:37.350
as high sensation
seeking, novelty seeking,

01:33:37.350 --> 01:33:39.070
they seem to want to
pair with one another.

01:33:39.070 --> 01:33:42.570
So there's a selection for similar,

01:33:42.570 --> 01:33:45.730
in two of the groups, autonomic tone.

01:33:45.730 --> 01:33:50.410
I find that very interesting
because in that decision

01:33:50.410 --> 01:33:53.430
or that preference for
similar autonomic tone,

01:33:53.430 --> 01:33:58.291
it essentially eliminates
a lot of the requirement

01:33:58.291 --> 01:34:01.990
for figuring out how to match

01:34:01.990 --> 01:34:03.344
one's autonomic nervous system to another.

01:34:03.344 --> 01:34:07.610
They simply find someone with
a similar tendency, okay?

01:34:07.610 --> 01:34:10.600
Whereas in the other two
groups that she called

01:34:10.600 --> 01:34:12.780
testosterone and estrogen,
the director type

01:34:12.780 --> 01:34:16.270
and the nurturing somewhat follower type,

01:34:16.270 --> 01:34:19.020
there's an establishment of balance,

01:34:19.020 --> 01:34:24.020
but not in between two who
individuals as a match,

01:34:24.050 --> 01:34:26.950
but rather on the whole
in the relationship.

01:34:26.950 --> 01:34:29.460
One person is driving the novelty seeking

01:34:29.460 --> 01:34:31.000
in the course of decisions and actions,

01:34:31.000 --> 01:34:33.850
and the other person is
essentially agreeing to those.

01:34:33.850 --> 01:34:37.290
Now, assuming that those decisions
are good for both people.

01:34:37.290 --> 01:34:39.250
And I emphasize good for both people,

01:34:39.250 --> 01:34:42.020
because one of the themes
that Dr. Fisher underscores,

01:34:42.020 --> 01:34:44.070
and I'd like to underscore here as well,

01:34:44.070 --> 01:34:48.830
is that it need not be the
case that people pair up

01:34:48.830 --> 01:34:51.030
exactly according to these categorizations

01:34:51.030 --> 01:34:53.740
that I've described,
dopamine with dopamine,

01:34:53.740 --> 01:34:56.197
serotonin with serotonin,
testosterone with estrogen,

01:34:56.197 --> 01:34:57.760
and so on.

01:34:57.760 --> 01:35:00.960
What is important is that
there be a recognition

01:35:00.960 --> 01:35:03.790
and a respect for the other types,

01:35:03.790 --> 01:35:06.580
or a recognition and a
respect for the fact that

01:35:06.580 --> 01:35:08.200
both are of the same type.

01:35:08.200 --> 01:35:10.820
You could actually imagine,
for instance, that two people

01:35:10.820 --> 01:35:14.060
of this high sensation
seeking, novelty seeking

01:35:14.060 --> 01:35:16.560
could have a terrifically
exciting relationship,

01:35:16.560 --> 01:35:20.410
but that it actually
might be a relationship

01:35:20.410 --> 01:35:23.670
in which the financial
stability isn't quite there,

01:35:23.670 --> 01:35:27.050
or in which the basic
stability isn't there.

01:35:27.050 --> 01:35:30.700
You could imagine, for
instance, a situation

01:35:30.700 --> 01:35:32.940
in which a relationship between two people

01:35:32.940 --> 01:35:37.220
of what she called the
high serotonin preference

01:35:37.220 --> 01:35:39.670
would have a relationship
that was actually dull,

01:35:39.670 --> 01:35:42.720
in which both of them found
themselves bored at some point,

01:35:42.720 --> 01:35:47.480
or in which there wasn't
enough of the dynamic tension

01:35:47.480 --> 01:35:51.040
that sometimes is required
in order to keep this cycle

01:35:51.040 --> 01:35:52.580
of desire, love, and attachment going.

01:35:52.580 --> 01:35:55.060
Something that we will
talk about in a moment.

01:35:55.060 --> 01:35:59.930
So the point here is not that
one should necessarily pair up

01:35:59.930 --> 01:36:02.940
according to these
arrangements that I described.

01:36:02.940 --> 01:36:06.630
The point is that on average,
that's what tends to happen.

01:36:06.630 --> 01:36:10.710
And that through a recognition
that these categorizations

01:36:10.710 --> 01:36:15.320
exist similar to the
recognition that the type

01:36:15.320 --> 01:36:19.970
A, B, C, and D infant and
toddler type attachments exist,

01:36:19.970 --> 01:36:23.690
that we can gain better
self-awareness of who we are

01:36:23.690 --> 01:36:26.830
and how we tend to show up
in romantic attachments,

01:36:26.830 --> 01:36:31.830
and thereby navigate
healthier mate seeking,

01:36:31.960 --> 01:36:36.420
healthier breakups, if
the case dictates it,

01:36:36.420 --> 01:36:39.380
and in some cases healthy
long-term relationships

01:36:39.380 --> 01:36:42.470
by understanding that the other
person can either be similar

01:36:42.470 --> 01:36:44.720
or complimentary to us.

01:36:44.720 --> 01:36:47.100
One is neither better than the other.

01:36:47.100 --> 01:36:50.720
It's simply the case that
in all romantic attachments,

01:36:50.720 --> 01:36:54.580
from the initial inception
of the romantic attachment,

01:36:54.580 --> 01:36:58.120
desire, love, and attachment,

01:36:58.120 --> 01:37:01.060
there is an autonomic coordination.

01:37:01.060 --> 01:37:03.250
And of course there's
coordination of all sorts

01:37:03.250 --> 01:37:07.900
of other things like food,
sex, and sleep, and finances,

01:37:07.900 --> 01:37:10.660
and where people are going to
live, and many other features,

01:37:10.660 --> 01:37:14.330
but that at the core of
all that is a seeking

01:37:14.330 --> 01:37:19.110
of either autonomic likeness
or autonomic differences.

01:37:19.110 --> 01:37:22.700
And I think that recognition
can be extremely valuable

01:37:22.700 --> 01:37:27.110
in thinking about tools to enter
and maintain relationships.

01:37:27.110 --> 01:37:30.430
If one thinks about their
autonomic nervous system,

01:37:30.430 --> 01:37:34.430
not simply as something that
is driven by external people

01:37:34.430 --> 01:37:37.970
and events, but that we can
actually gain some control over

01:37:37.970 --> 01:37:40.440
through techniques of the sort
that I talked about earlier

01:37:40.440 --> 01:37:41.880
and on previous podcasts,

01:37:41.880 --> 01:37:45.170
but also generally, if
we are able to adjust

01:37:45.170 --> 01:37:49.230
our autonomic nervous system
in order to at least appreciate

01:37:49.230 --> 01:37:53.160
or get some empathy into what
someone else is experiencing,

01:37:53.160 --> 01:37:56.420
then we gain actual cognitive empathy.

01:37:56.420 --> 01:38:00.130
And this episode isn't
about empathy per se,

01:38:00.130 --> 01:38:01.920
but the theme keeps
coming up again and again.

01:38:01.920 --> 01:38:04.330
And I think it's worth
mentioning that when you talk

01:38:04.330 --> 01:38:07.420
to psychologists, whether
or not they're psychoanalyst

01:38:07.420 --> 01:38:10.010
or from another source of training,

01:38:10.010 --> 01:38:12.350
what you find is that they
don't talk about empathy

01:38:12.350 --> 01:38:16.670
as a general term, they will
talk about emotional empathy,

01:38:16.670 --> 01:38:18.340
they'll talk about cognitive empathy.

01:38:18.340 --> 01:38:20.250
And what I'm talking
about here today is that

01:38:20.250 --> 01:38:24.210
yet a third category that
is very strongly determinant

01:38:24.210 --> 01:38:27.960
of relationship dynamics,
and that's autonomic empathy.

01:38:27.960 --> 01:38:30.640
I'm a biologist, I'm not a psychologist.

01:38:30.640 --> 01:38:32.350
So I love mechanism.

01:38:32.350 --> 01:38:35.700
And fortunately there are
studies that have been done

01:38:35.700 --> 01:38:37.880
recently using modern techniques

01:38:37.880 --> 01:38:41.630
to look at neural mechanisms
of romantic attachment.

01:38:41.630 --> 01:38:44.810
I mentioned earlier some of
the brain imaging studies

01:38:44.810 --> 01:38:49.760
that have been done on child
and mother literally imaging

01:38:49.760 --> 01:38:52.840
the activity of neurons in
the brain as child is nursing,

01:38:52.840 --> 01:38:55.000
or as a mother is soothing baby,

01:38:55.000 --> 01:38:59.450
and as you learned earlier,
baby is soothing mother as well.

01:38:59.450 --> 01:39:00.420
Those are remarkable studies.

01:39:00.420 --> 01:39:02.120
You may have seen some
of these pictures online.

01:39:02.120 --> 01:39:04.570
You can see the silhouette
of the infant and mother,

01:39:04.570 --> 01:39:07.370
and their brains and even
some of the brain activation

01:39:07.370 --> 01:39:09.630
patterns, really, really
beautiful studies.

01:39:09.630 --> 01:39:13.930
Similar studies have been
done in romantic couples

01:39:13.930 --> 01:39:17.170
with those couples, either
touching one another,

01:39:17.170 --> 01:39:20.720
touching and kissing,
or in clever, I think,

01:39:20.720 --> 01:39:23.284
control experiments of the
person just touching a pillow,

01:39:23.284 --> 01:39:26.460
[laughs] or something, or kissing a pillow

01:39:26.460 --> 01:39:30.510
in order to try and create
the most reasonable control

01:39:30.510 --> 01:39:31.960
for what are actually pretty

01:39:31.960 --> 01:39:33.436
complicated interpersonal dynamics

01:39:33.436 --> 01:39:35.663
to do in a brain imaging scanner.

01:39:36.770 --> 01:39:40.070
But some of the other studies
that have been done recently

01:39:40.070 --> 01:39:41.270
involved so called EEG.

01:39:41.270 --> 01:39:42.960
So these are electrical recordings

01:39:42.960 --> 01:39:44.930
that are done noninvasively,

01:39:44.930 --> 01:39:47.570
putting a bunch of electrodes
on the outside of the scalp.

01:39:47.570 --> 01:39:52.340
EEG is useful in that you
can do it noninvasively,

01:39:52.340 --> 01:39:56.380
you can do it while people
are moving and doing things,

01:39:56.380 --> 01:39:58.850
kissing, touching, et cetera.

01:39:58.850 --> 01:40:03.160
It doesn't allow one to image
or to evaluate neural activity

01:40:03.160 --> 01:40:04.640
very deeply in the brain.

01:40:04.640 --> 01:40:06.390
So you can miss out on a lot of things.

01:40:06.390 --> 01:40:08.920
It's like looking at the
wave structure on the ocean

01:40:08.920 --> 01:40:12.320
without actually looking
into the depths of the ocean.

01:40:12.320 --> 01:40:13.640
So you can miss certain things,

01:40:13.640 --> 01:40:17.020
but if you see things generally
you trust they're there,

01:40:17.020 --> 01:40:18.660
but you can't see what you don't see.

01:40:18.660 --> 01:40:21.090
Nonetheless, there's some studies

01:40:21.090 --> 01:40:24.660
that I'll just point you
to and that form the segue

01:40:24.660 --> 01:40:27.440
for what I'm going to discuss in a moment,

01:40:27.440 --> 01:40:32.440
which is a study published in
Scientific Reports in 2021,

01:40:33.080 --> 01:40:35.280
entitled "Investigating Real Life Emotions

01:40:35.280 --> 01:40:37.960
in Romantic Couples: a Mobile EEG Study."

01:40:37.960 --> 01:40:41.880
So this is, as the title
suggests, having people wear

01:40:41.880 --> 01:40:46.880
these EEG caps of electrodes,
get engage in very passionate,

01:40:47.360 --> 01:40:50.560
emotional kisses, emotional
speech toward one another

01:40:50.560 --> 01:40:51.710
standing at different distances.

01:40:51.710 --> 01:40:54.160
So a lot of cool stuff that
you can do that you really

01:40:54.160 --> 01:40:56.870
couldn't do in a brain scanner,
because in a brain scanner,

01:40:56.870 --> 01:40:58.970
people have to be there
usually in a bite bar,

01:40:58.970 --> 01:41:00.430
they're actually jaw flicked like this.

01:41:00.430 --> 01:41:02.420
I've been in one of these things.

01:41:02.420 --> 01:41:03.850
There's not a lot of
moving around to be heard,

01:41:03.850 --> 01:41:07.070
at least not using the current technology.

01:41:07.070 --> 01:41:09.510
In any case, what they found was

01:41:09.510 --> 01:41:14.230
there is a shift in brain
waves, brain states,

01:41:14.230 --> 01:41:16.760
things like alpha waves or
just a particular frequency

01:41:16.760 --> 01:41:19.540
of brain waves in the
neocortex, the outer shell

01:41:19.540 --> 01:41:22.190
of the brain just beneath the skull.

01:41:22.190 --> 01:41:26.680
And in people that are kissing
or in people that are engaged

01:41:26.680 --> 01:41:31.190
in romantic speech, or I didn't
actually hear what they said

01:41:31.190 --> 01:41:34.540
to one another, but what
the couple seems exciting,

01:41:34.540 --> 01:41:38.160
romantic and arousing to
them, they see more alpha wave

01:41:38.160 --> 01:41:40.330
activity compared to
the control conditions.

01:41:40.330 --> 01:41:42.700
And there was some what
we call lateralization,

01:41:42.700 --> 01:41:44.750
where the left hemisphere was
more active than the right

01:41:44.750 --> 01:41:45.583
and so forth.

01:41:46.780 --> 01:41:50.430
And these studies are
important because we know that

01:41:50.430 --> 01:41:53.450
the autonomic nervous
systems of individuals tend

01:41:53.450 --> 01:41:58.030
to start to collaborate
and actually synchronize

01:41:58.030 --> 01:42:01.260
at the level of heartbeats,
at the level of breathing

01:42:01.260 --> 01:42:03.600
during romantic interactions
of different kinds.

01:42:03.600 --> 01:42:05.290
But these studies are some of the first

01:42:05.290 --> 01:42:06.550
of their kind to start looking

01:42:06.550 --> 01:42:09.920
at neural synchronization
between individuals.

01:42:09.920 --> 01:42:14.270
Now, the simple version of looking at this

01:42:14.270 --> 01:42:17.210
and the way I would've
thought this would all go was,

01:42:17.210 --> 01:42:19.640
okay, two people start
kissing, they start talking

01:42:19.640 --> 01:42:21.590
about what they find particularly romantic

01:42:21.590 --> 01:42:22.423
and arousing for them.

01:42:22.423 --> 01:42:24.850
And their brain waves will
just match to one another.

01:42:24.850 --> 01:42:28.377
And that's really the basis
of romantic attachment

01:42:28.377 --> 01:42:32.300
and romantic engagement
in that sort of thing.

01:42:32.300 --> 01:42:36.330
But it turns out that
the opposite is true.

01:42:36.330 --> 01:42:40.850
So a really nice study published
in a really fine journal,

01:42:40.850 --> 01:42:42.850
Cerebral Cortex is a
journal that I've known

01:42:42.850 --> 01:42:44.840
about for many years, they
published strong anatomy,

01:42:44.840 --> 01:42:46.780
physiology and neuroimaging.

01:42:46.780 --> 01:42:50.703
There's a study that was
published, first author, Kajimura,

01:42:52.590 --> 01:42:54.600
and this paper really points...

01:42:54.600 --> 01:42:56.990
Again, this is 2021.

01:42:56.990 --> 01:42:58.627
And the title of this paper is,

01:42:58.627 --> 01:43:01.110
"Brain Knows Who Is on
the Same Wavelength:

01:43:01.110 --> 01:43:04.050
Resting-State Connectivity
Can Predict Compatibility

01:43:04.050 --> 01:43:06.410
of a Female-Male Relationship."

01:43:06.410 --> 01:43:08.840
Now what this study did
was a little bit different.

01:43:08.840 --> 01:43:11.750
They looked at the resting or default mode

01:43:11.750 --> 01:43:12.890
activity of the brain.

01:43:12.890 --> 01:43:15.920
So rather than evoked
activity, as it's called,

01:43:15.920 --> 01:43:19.440
where people are kissing or
are engaged in some activity,

01:43:19.440 --> 01:43:24.170
this was a neuroimaging
study, not EEG, but fMRI,

01:43:24.170 --> 01:43:25.830
functional magnetic resonance imaging,

01:43:25.830 --> 01:43:29.190
which is similar to EEG in principle,

01:43:29.190 --> 01:43:31.410
but allows you to look
deep into the brain.

01:43:31.410 --> 01:43:35.490
And it has a very good
resolution in time and space.

01:43:35.490 --> 01:43:40.000
So fast events can be monitored
and the precise location

01:43:40.000 --> 01:43:43.640
of those events can be monitored
somewhat better than EEG.

01:43:43.640 --> 01:43:44.780
And there are exceptions to this.

01:43:44.780 --> 01:43:46.380
So for you EEGers out there.

01:43:46.380 --> 01:43:50.370
EEG don't come after me with electrodes.

01:43:50.370 --> 01:43:54.200
Just understand that fMRI
gives you a fuller picture

01:43:54.200 --> 01:43:55.150
of what's going on.

01:43:55.150 --> 01:43:59.550
And what Kajimura et al
found was that contrary

01:43:59.550 --> 01:44:03.883
to what your reflexive
prediction might be,

01:44:05.010 --> 01:44:10.010
people tend to select people
that have resting brain states

01:44:10.080 --> 01:44:11.990
that different than theirs,

01:44:11.990 --> 01:44:15.240
or sometimes they found
that are actually opposite

01:44:15.240 --> 01:44:17.310
to their own resting brain state.

01:44:17.310 --> 01:44:19.360
And you might say, "Well,
that doesn't make any sense.

01:44:19.360 --> 01:44:22.290
I thought this is all about
autonomic coordination."

01:44:22.290 --> 01:44:25.702
But actually if we go back to
Helen Fisher's categorizations

01:44:25.702 --> 01:44:28.650
of the dopamine types, the
sensation seeking types,

01:44:28.650 --> 01:44:33.210
that is serotonin, the
stable rule following types,

01:44:33.210 --> 01:44:34.530
testosterone and estrogen types,

01:44:34.530 --> 01:44:36.910
remember that the two
categories that she called

01:44:36.910 --> 01:44:38.180
testosterone and estrogen type,

01:44:38.180 --> 01:44:40.720
the director and the
follower, the nurturer,

01:44:40.720 --> 01:44:42.180
I guess it would be the more accurate way,

01:44:42.180 --> 01:44:43.940
the director and the nurturer,

01:44:43.940 --> 01:44:46.750
those tend to pair up across categories,

01:44:46.750 --> 01:44:48.460
not within category.

01:44:48.460 --> 01:44:51.460
And so I think what's
really needed for this field

01:44:51.460 --> 01:44:53.700
which to my knowledge hasn't happened yet,

01:44:53.700 --> 01:44:58.057
is to really start to
map the neuroanatomical

01:44:58.057 --> 01:45:01.160
and neurophysiological
findings of, in this case,

01:45:01.160 --> 01:45:06.160
that resting brain state is
in one form in one individual,

01:45:06.790 --> 01:45:09.290
and they tend to seek out
people whose resting brain state

01:45:09.290 --> 01:45:11.930
is different than theirs, not similar.

01:45:11.930 --> 01:45:15.530
That needs to be mapped
onto the more subjective

01:45:15.530 --> 01:45:19.370
psychological categorizations
that Helen Fisher

01:45:19.370 --> 01:45:22.020
and indeed the Gottman's
and others have created,

01:45:22.020 --> 01:45:24.030
that sort of the state of the field now.

01:45:24.030 --> 01:45:26.430
And I mentioned this not to confuse you,

01:45:26.430 --> 01:45:30.060
but to the contrary, to
illustrate that it's not just

01:45:30.060 --> 01:45:32.100
about finding someone just like you,

01:45:32.100 --> 01:45:34.430
and it's not just about finding someone

01:45:34.430 --> 01:45:35.920
who's opposite to you.

01:45:35.920 --> 01:45:38.030
This is actually the reason
that I decided to become

01:45:38.030 --> 01:45:41.620
a biologist at some point
in my life, which is that

01:45:41.620 --> 01:45:44.610
we can find verbal sayings,
and stories, and examples

01:45:44.610 --> 01:45:46.373
to support just about anything.

01:45:47.220 --> 01:45:49.180
This is not a knock on
the field of psychology,

01:45:49.180 --> 01:45:50.870
as you can probably tell
from today's episode.

01:45:50.870 --> 01:45:52.610
I have great respect for in reverence

01:45:52.610 --> 01:45:55.990
for the field of psychology,
especially its collaboration

01:45:55.990 --> 01:45:58.100
with neuroscience and vice versa.

01:45:58.100 --> 01:46:00.750
But in the popular culture,

01:46:00.750 --> 01:46:04.040
we can find examples and
sayings that support essentially

01:46:04.040 --> 01:46:06.400
anything as it relates to a relationship.

01:46:06.400 --> 01:46:08.900
For instance, I've heard
and you've probably heard,

01:46:08.900 --> 01:46:10.900
absence makes the heart grow fonder.

01:46:10.900 --> 01:46:14.010
And indeed I've experienced
that and I believe it's true.

01:46:14.010 --> 01:46:16.410
But I also have experienced
and I believe to be true

01:46:16.410 --> 01:46:18.830
that out of sight out of mind also exists

01:46:18.830 --> 01:46:21.690
and that there will be a
biological mechanism for that.

01:46:21.690 --> 01:46:24.800
The point here is that
matching of same to same

01:46:24.800 --> 01:46:27.558
or same to different can
both be effective in creating

01:46:27.558 --> 01:46:32.558
the desire, love, attachment process.

01:46:32.880 --> 01:46:36.160
It's a matter of, who is looking for same,

01:46:36.160 --> 01:46:37.390
and who is looking for different?

01:46:37.390 --> 01:46:40.150
And there, I think Dr. Fisher and the work

01:46:40.150 --> 01:46:42.730
of these neurophysiologist
and brain imagers

01:46:42.730 --> 01:46:45.250
really does point in a direction whereby

01:46:45.250 --> 01:46:48.960
there is not one form of attachment

01:46:48.960 --> 01:46:51.280
that is going to be
wholly above [indistinct]

01:46:51.280 --> 01:46:53.120
will predict good outcomes.

01:46:53.120 --> 01:46:56.550
There is not going to be a case
in which opposites attract,

01:46:56.550 --> 01:46:58.153
and that's always the best rule to follow.

01:46:58.153 --> 01:47:01.320
Sometimes it will, sometimes it won't.

01:47:01.320 --> 01:47:03.320
There is also not the
case that people tend

01:47:03.320 --> 01:47:05.340
to pair up with similar.

01:47:05.340 --> 01:47:08.140
Sometimes it will be the
case, sometimes it won't.

01:47:08.140 --> 01:47:09.673
Now there are certain statistics

01:47:09.673 --> 01:47:11.360
that support that statement.

01:47:11.360 --> 01:47:13.690
For instance, people, on average,

01:47:13.690 --> 01:47:17.320
people pair up with individuals
of similar educational

01:47:17.320 --> 01:47:19.170
background, income, and attractiveness.

01:47:19.170 --> 01:47:22.420
That is true on average, but
it's not always the case.

01:47:22.420 --> 01:47:26.150
And again, a knowledge of and
a respect for the different

01:47:26.150 --> 01:47:28.786
categorizations of attachment,
the different categorizations

01:47:28.786 --> 01:47:31.610
of mate seeking described
by Fisher and others,

01:47:31.610 --> 01:47:34.390
and the recognition that
matching of autonomic nervous

01:47:34.390 --> 01:47:38.600
systems but also mismatching
of resting state brain networks

01:47:38.600 --> 01:47:41.650
are all at play in driving
what we are calling

01:47:41.650 --> 01:47:43.490
desire, love and attachment.

01:47:43.490 --> 01:47:45.660
So in keeping with the
exploration of the fact that

01:47:45.660 --> 01:47:49.320
there's a saying, or a book,
or a song, or an example

01:47:49.320 --> 01:47:51.483
of pretty much any relationship dynamic,

01:47:52.320 --> 01:47:55.500
I want to now talk about an
article that came out a little

01:47:55.500 --> 01:48:00.500
over 10 years ago that talked
about the universality of love

01:48:01.410 --> 01:48:02.850
and the ability to fall in love.

01:48:02.850 --> 01:48:04.160
So this would be very much in line

01:48:04.160 --> 01:48:06.610
with the George Bernard Shaw
quote that I mentioned earlier

01:48:06.610 --> 01:48:09.130
that "Love is really overestimating

01:48:09.130 --> 01:48:10.670
the differences between individuals."

01:48:10.670 --> 01:48:12.160
And again, I should say
that is not something

01:48:12.160 --> 01:48:13.720
that I personally believe,

01:48:13.720 --> 01:48:15.630
although maybe I'm just diluting myself.

01:48:15.630 --> 01:48:18.380
I like to think that the
people that we fall in love

01:48:18.380 --> 01:48:21.980
with are really special for us,

01:48:21.980 --> 01:48:25.630
that they could not easily be
replaced with anybody else.

01:48:25.630 --> 01:48:26.980
That's simply my stance.

01:48:26.980 --> 01:48:27.870
I'm not basing that

01:48:27.870 --> 01:48:31.610
on any hardcore neurobiological mechanism.

01:48:31.610 --> 01:48:35.240
But nonetheless, an article was published

01:48:35.240 --> 01:48:38.390
in The New York Times in 2015 that related

01:48:38.390 --> 01:48:42.420
to some psychological
studies that were done,

01:48:42.420 --> 01:48:44.610
as well as some clinical
work, as well as some,

01:48:44.610 --> 01:48:48.180
what I would call pop
psychology or things that fall

01:48:48.180 --> 01:48:50.730
outside the domains of academic science.

01:48:50.730 --> 01:48:55.340
And the whole basis of this article was

01:48:56.330 --> 01:48:58.980
36 questions that lead to love.

01:48:58.980 --> 01:49:03.420
And it involved a listing
out indeed of 36 questions,

01:49:03.420 --> 01:49:07.170
divided into set one, set two,
and set three that progressed

01:49:07.170 --> 01:49:11.390
from somewhat ordinary
questions about life experience

01:49:11.390 --> 01:49:13.743
and self-report to more,

01:49:14.640 --> 01:49:18.142
let's call them deep questions
about people's values

01:49:18.142 --> 01:49:20.240
and things that are
emotionally close to them.

01:49:20.240 --> 01:49:21.990
And I'll just give an
example of a few of these.

01:49:21.990 --> 01:49:24.690
You can find this easily
online by just putting

01:49:24.690 --> 01:49:27.960
into your search engine, 36
questions that lead to love.

01:49:27.960 --> 01:49:31.720
Some of the questions in set
number one, where for instance,

01:49:31.720 --> 01:49:34.043
what would constitute
a perfect day for you?

01:49:35.400 --> 01:49:37.120
For what in your life do
you feel most grateful?

01:49:37.120 --> 01:49:38.690
Kind of standard questionnaire stuff.

01:49:38.690 --> 01:49:41.970
In set two, what is your
most treasured memory?

01:49:41.970 --> 01:49:43.420
What is your most terrible memory?

01:49:43.420 --> 01:49:46.020
So these, as you can tell, are
drilling a little bit deeper

01:49:46.020 --> 01:49:49.270
into one's personal experience
and emotional system.

01:49:49.270 --> 01:49:54.270
And then set three, questions
25 through 36 are things,

01:49:56.550 --> 01:50:00.280
what is a very embarrassing
moment in your life?

01:50:00.280 --> 01:50:03.127
When did you last cry in
front of another person

01:50:03.127 --> 01:50:04.970
and by yourself?

01:50:04.970 --> 01:50:07.110
What is something that's too
serious to be joked about?

01:50:07.110 --> 01:50:11.010
So it's going deeper into
one's emotional system.

01:50:11.010 --> 01:50:13.780
And even questions like, of
all the people in your family,

01:50:13.780 --> 01:50:16.690
whose death would you find
most disturbing and why?

01:50:16.690 --> 01:50:19.200
So pretty, pretty heavy
stuff there at the end.

01:50:19.200 --> 01:50:21.760
Now, the reason this article
got so much traction,

01:50:21.760 --> 01:50:23.850
and the reason I'm bringing
it up today is that

01:50:23.850 --> 01:50:27.440
there was a statement that
was made in and around

01:50:27.440 --> 01:50:32.410
this article that if two
people went on a date

01:50:32.410 --> 01:50:36.520
or simply sat down and asked
each other these questions,

01:50:36.520 --> 01:50:41.520
and each answered these questions
and the other was paying

01:50:41.970 --> 01:50:46.970
attention carefully and at some
level emotionally responding

01:50:47.240 --> 01:50:48.683
or not out responding, but
certainly paying attention

01:50:48.683 --> 01:50:51.180
to the answers of the other person,

01:50:51.180 --> 01:50:55.800
that by the end of that
exchange, where one person asks

01:50:55.800 --> 01:50:58.610
36 questions and the other
person answers all 36,

01:50:58.610 --> 01:51:01.920
and then the other person asks
all 36 and the other person

01:51:01.920 --> 01:51:05.660
answers all 36, that they
would fall in love, right?

01:51:05.660 --> 01:51:07.970
Which seems like a ridiculous thing.

01:51:07.970 --> 01:51:11.950
And yet it is the case that people who go

01:51:11.950 --> 01:51:16.400
through this exercise report
feeling as if they know

01:51:16.400 --> 01:51:20.600
the other person quite well
and feeling certain levels

01:51:20.600 --> 01:51:23.800
of attachment or even love and
desire for the other person

01:51:23.800 --> 01:51:27.230
that they were, would not
have predicted, excuse me,

01:51:27.230 --> 01:51:29.260
would not have predicted

01:51:29.260 --> 01:51:31.220
had they not gone through that process.

01:51:31.220 --> 01:51:32.578
So what's going on in
this exchange of questions

01:51:32.578 --> 01:51:36.670
and answers of a
progressively more emotional

01:51:36.670 --> 01:51:38.580
and deep level?

01:51:38.580 --> 01:51:41.310
Well, what I predict is
going on is that inside

01:51:41.310 --> 01:51:46.130
of that exchange, people are
creating a delusional story

01:51:46.130 --> 01:51:49.600
about the nature of the
exchange being a reflection

01:51:49.600 --> 01:51:51.280
of some deeper attachment.

01:51:51.280 --> 01:51:54.010
And so even though people
are just exchanging words,

01:51:54.010 --> 01:51:57.770
they're not physically touching,
they are not, at least not

01:51:57.770 --> 01:52:00.738
at the point where they're
running these kinds

01:52:00.738 --> 01:52:02.563
of questionnaire studies.

01:52:03.510 --> 01:52:05.400
They may touch afterwards for all I know,

01:52:05.400 --> 01:52:06.734
and probably did in some cases,

01:52:06.734 --> 01:52:09.780
but they're not exchanging life experience

01:52:09.780 --> 01:52:11.350
in an immediate way.

01:52:11.350 --> 01:52:13.190
They're not actually
going off into the world

01:52:13.190 --> 01:52:15.060
and doing things together yet.

01:52:15.060 --> 01:52:17.840
They are simply exchanging narrative.

01:52:17.840 --> 01:52:21.760
But we know based on recent
studies and I've covered

01:52:21.760 --> 01:52:24.190
this before on this podcast,
but I'll mention again,

01:52:24.190 --> 01:52:27.260
there was a study
published in Cell Reports,

01:52:27.260 --> 01:52:29.400
a Cell Press journal, excellent journal

01:52:29.400 --> 01:52:33.930
showing that when individuals
listen to the same narrative,

01:52:33.930 --> 01:52:35.147
their heart rates tend to synchronize

01:52:35.147 --> 01:52:37.800
or at least follow a very similar pattern,

01:52:37.800 --> 01:52:39.510
even if they're not in the same room

01:52:39.510 --> 01:52:41.150
listening to a given narrative.

01:52:41.150 --> 01:52:44.210
Whereas in this case, people
are facing one another

01:52:44.210 --> 01:52:46.690
listening to the narratives of each other.

01:52:46.690 --> 01:52:49.960
Certainly they are having
autonomic responses.

01:52:49.960 --> 01:52:53.150
And it stands to reason that
their autonomic nervous systems

01:52:53.150 --> 01:52:55.250
are synchronizing much
in the same way that

01:52:55.250 --> 01:52:58.410
the Cell Report study found
that people will synchronize

01:52:58.410 --> 01:53:01.740
their autonomic nervous
systems to a shared,

01:53:01.740 --> 01:53:03.850
heard story from another.

01:53:03.850 --> 01:53:06.280
In other words, whether
or not we hear a story,

01:53:06.280 --> 01:53:08.520
watch a movie, listen to a song,

01:53:08.520 --> 01:53:11.330
or exchange our own individual stories,

01:53:11.330 --> 01:53:13.600
our autonomic nervous
systems have the potential

01:53:13.600 --> 01:53:15.040
to map onto one another.

01:53:15.040 --> 01:53:18.860
So I'm not all that
surprised that people find

01:53:18.860 --> 01:53:21.870
that they fall in love, in quotes,

01:53:21.870 --> 01:53:24.240
after answering these
questions to one another,

01:53:24.240 --> 01:53:25.880
because essentially
the way these questions

01:53:25.880 --> 01:53:28.980
are laid out is they
establish a narrative.

01:53:28.980 --> 01:53:30.930
They establish a very personal narrative

01:53:30.930 --> 01:53:32.277
and the other person is
listening very closely.

01:53:32.277 --> 01:53:35.970
And we don't have physiological
or brain imaging studies

01:53:35.970 --> 01:53:38.670
to support what I'm about to say,

01:53:38.670 --> 01:53:42.120
but the reasonable interpretation is that

01:53:42.120 --> 01:53:45.470
that's causing some
autonomic synchronization.

01:53:45.470 --> 01:53:48.800
So if you want to try this on
a date or even it's actually

01:53:48.800 --> 01:53:51.400
been hypothesized that
this could be useful

01:53:51.400 --> 01:53:54.990
for existing couples, even if
they already know the answers

01:53:54.990 --> 01:53:56.050
to some of these questions.

01:53:56.050 --> 01:53:57.780
And that doesn't surprise me either.

01:53:57.780 --> 01:53:59.850
I think the autonomic
coordination is present

01:53:59.850 --> 01:54:02.440
during mating behavior,

01:54:02.440 --> 01:54:05.910
it's present during shared
experience of the outside world,

01:54:05.910 --> 01:54:08.810
movies, concerts, watching one's children

01:54:08.810 --> 01:54:10.031
with somebody else, et cetera.

01:54:10.031 --> 01:54:13.450
And it's established by
sharing one's own narrative

01:54:13.450 --> 01:54:15.170
of their own personal experience.

01:54:15.170 --> 01:54:17.430
So I don't want to seem
overly reductionist.

01:54:17.430 --> 01:54:21.530
I'll never propose that all
of our sensation, perception,

01:54:21.530 --> 01:54:25.020
action and experience in life
boils down to us just being

01:54:25.020 --> 01:54:28.060
bags of chemicals and the
action of those chemicals,

01:54:28.060 --> 01:54:29.253
or any aspect of our nervous system.

01:54:29.253 --> 01:54:34.253
And yet in looking across
the psychological literature

01:54:34.560 --> 01:54:37.190
of development of attachment,
in the psychological

01:54:37.190 --> 01:54:40.090
literature of adult and
romantic attachment,

01:54:40.090 --> 01:54:43.410
and what makes and
breaks those attachments,

01:54:43.410 --> 01:54:44.880
it's very clear to me.

01:54:44.880 --> 01:54:48.400
And I think courses through
the literature multiple levels,

01:54:48.400 --> 01:54:52.410
that autonomic coordination
is absolutely key

01:54:52.410 --> 01:54:55.660
for the establishment of
desire, love and attachment.

01:54:55.660 --> 01:54:58.580
In fact, I talked earlier
about how our actual conception

01:54:58.580 --> 01:55:00.870
is born out of autonomic coordination

01:55:00.870 --> 01:55:02.600
of one sort or another.

01:55:02.600 --> 01:55:06.500
So again, it doesn't necessarily
mean that autonomic nervous

01:55:06.500 --> 01:55:09.460
systems always be synchronized
in the case of the two

01:55:09.460 --> 01:55:11.820
categorizations that Fisher proposed

01:55:11.820 --> 01:55:14.380
of the director/testosterone type

01:55:14.380 --> 01:55:19.380
and the nurturing follower/estrogen type.

01:55:20.220 --> 01:55:24.670
It was actually the coordination
but in opposite directions

01:55:24.670 --> 01:55:27.330
of individuals that fall
into each of those categories

01:55:27.330 --> 01:55:28.643
that led to more stable attachments

01:55:28.643 --> 01:55:31.840
or the seeking out of those
attachments, I should say.

01:55:31.840 --> 01:55:35.610
But nonetheless, it's, at
least to my mind, very clear

01:55:35.610 --> 01:55:39.390
that autonomic coordination
is a hallmark feature

01:55:39.390 --> 01:55:44.250
of desire, a hallmark
feature of what we call love,

01:55:44.250 --> 01:55:47.110
and a hallmark feature of
what we call attachment.

01:55:47.110 --> 01:55:51.060
And that the breaking of
attachments were the failures

01:55:51.060 --> 01:55:53.950
of desire, the failures of love,

01:55:53.950 --> 01:55:56.740
and the failures of attachment over time

01:55:56.740 --> 01:55:58.660
in line with the work
of Gottman and others.

01:55:58.660 --> 01:56:02.570
And in even just simply what's
required for mating behavior

01:56:02.570 --> 01:56:05.700
is also reflected in the
autonomic nervous system.

01:56:05.700 --> 01:56:07.910
But in that case, a failure to coordinate

01:56:07.910 --> 01:56:11.380
the autonomic nervous systems
in some sort of concerted way.

01:56:11.380 --> 01:56:14.240
Any discussion about
desire, love, and attachment

01:56:14.240 --> 01:56:15.960
would be incomplete

01:56:15.960 --> 01:56:20.420
if we didn't talk about the
dreaded infidelity and cheating.

01:56:20.420 --> 01:56:22.360
Much has been made of
infidelity and cheating

01:56:22.360 --> 01:56:24.850
and whether or not people
who are higher on dopamine

01:56:24.850 --> 01:56:27.410
and sensation seeking tend
to cheat more or less.

01:56:27.410 --> 01:56:30.723
Frankly, I don't think there's
any solid evidence for that.

01:56:31.750 --> 01:56:33.710
I think there are a lot of
examples that we can draw

01:56:33.710 --> 01:56:36.830
from in our own lives and
in the lives of others

01:56:36.830 --> 01:56:39.590
that would generally support
one or the other model,

01:56:39.590 --> 01:56:43.410
but I'm not aware of any
decent physiological studies

01:56:43.410 --> 01:56:46.290
or psychological studies
that really point to that.

01:56:46.290 --> 01:56:50.060
For instance, I would never
say that the serotonergic

01:56:50.060 --> 01:56:54.800
phenotype as described by
Fisher is less prone to cheat,

01:56:54.800 --> 01:56:58.630
or that the people who
have an insecure attachment

01:56:58.630 --> 01:57:02.010
are more likely to cheat,
et cetera, for instance.

01:57:02.010 --> 01:57:04.450
I don't think those
correlations have been drawn

01:57:04.450 --> 01:57:05.880
in any kind of meaningful way yet.

01:57:05.880 --> 01:57:09.330
So I would be cautious
about assigning them

01:57:09.330 --> 01:57:11.400
without that evidence.

01:57:11.400 --> 01:57:14.640
However, there are some
interesting studies involving,

01:57:14.640 --> 01:57:18.900
again, neuroimaging and some
subjective measures in humans,

01:57:18.900 --> 01:57:20.330
meaning asking them questions

01:57:20.330 --> 01:57:23.810
that they're good ways to
tease out lies from truths

01:57:23.810 --> 01:57:28.280
in these sorts of studies and
whether or not people tend

01:57:28.280 --> 01:57:33.280
to find their partner or
others more or less attractive

01:57:33.500 --> 01:57:36.480
depending on how people
feel about themselves.

01:57:36.480 --> 01:57:39.470
And I think this is a
very interesting aspect

01:57:39.470 --> 01:57:42.403
to desire, love, and attachment
for the following reason.

01:57:43.920 --> 01:57:47.140
You hear a lot out out there that in order

01:57:47.140 --> 01:57:49.950
to form a really strong relationship,

01:57:49.950 --> 01:57:51.842
you have to have a good
relationship with yourself,

01:57:51.842 --> 01:57:54.420
or you have to love yourself.

01:57:54.420 --> 01:57:59.420
Or you often hear for instance
that it's exactly when you're

01:57:59.730 --> 01:58:02.020
not looking for a relationship
that you're going to find one.

01:58:02.020 --> 01:58:03.430
You hear this stuff, right?

01:58:03.430 --> 01:58:05.800
But none of that is really
grounded in any studies.

01:58:05.800 --> 01:58:07.041
Again, that's like out
of sight out of mind,

01:58:07.041 --> 01:58:09.360
or absence makes the heart grow fonder.

01:58:09.360 --> 01:58:13.500
There are many life examples
to support those statements.

01:58:13.500 --> 01:58:14.917
And there are many life examples

01:58:14.917 --> 01:58:17.233
to support statements to the opposite.

01:58:19.070 --> 01:58:21.700
There's a particular study that I found.

01:58:21.700 --> 01:58:23.950
This was published in
Frontiers in Psychology,

01:58:23.950 --> 01:58:28.020
but it's a experimental study
that involves neuroimaging.

01:58:28.020 --> 01:58:31.780
The title of this study is
"Manipulation of Self-Expansion

01:58:31.780 --> 01:58:35.500
Alters Responses to Attractive
Alternative Partners."

01:58:35.500 --> 01:58:37.190
And I love the design of this study.

01:58:37.190 --> 01:58:40.540
What they did in this
study is they took couples

01:58:40.540 --> 01:58:44.560
and they evaluated members
of that relationship

01:58:44.560 --> 01:58:46.078
for what's called self-expansion.

01:58:46.078 --> 01:58:50.540
Now self-expansion is
a metric that involves

01:58:51.840 --> 01:58:53.380
one's perception of self

01:58:53.380 --> 01:58:56.830
as seen through the
relationship to the other.

01:58:56.830 --> 01:58:59.900
And this is something
that was developed by,

01:58:59.900 --> 01:59:02.380
the authors are Aron and Aron.

01:59:02.380 --> 01:59:03.480
So they have the same last name.

01:59:03.480 --> 01:59:05.950
So I'm assuming this was
either a sibling team

01:59:05.950 --> 01:59:10.210
or a somehow related team
or a romantic couple team.

01:59:10.210 --> 01:59:15.210
A-R-O-N and A-R-O-N,
Aron and Aron, in 1986,

01:59:15.780 --> 01:59:18.710
proposed this self-expansion
model of close relationships.

01:59:18.710 --> 01:59:20.640
And they proposed "That
people are motivated

01:59:20.640 --> 01:59:21.720
to enter relationships..."

01:59:21.720 --> 01:59:22.553
I'm reading here.

01:59:22.553 --> 01:59:25.830
"In order to enhance the self
and increase self-efficacy."

01:59:25.830 --> 01:59:28.780
In other words, that one of
the reasons why many people

01:59:28.780 --> 01:59:31.100
enter relationships is
that it makes us feel good

01:59:31.100 --> 01:59:32.460
about ourselves and more capable.

01:59:32.460 --> 01:59:34.900
And I would see that as a
healthy interdependence,

01:59:34.900 --> 01:59:36.623
not necessarily codependence.

01:59:38.380 --> 01:59:39.961
This is especially strong at the beginning

01:59:39.961 --> 01:59:41.590
of a relationship, it turns out,

01:59:41.590 --> 01:59:43.690
when people are forming pair bonds,

01:59:43.690 --> 01:59:48.340
and it's the case that pleasure,
arousal and excitement,

01:59:48.340 --> 01:59:50.690
again, all hallmark features

01:59:50.690 --> 01:59:52.490
of autonomic nervous system function,

01:59:52.490 --> 01:59:54.543
pleasure, arousal and excitement,

01:59:55.420 --> 01:59:59.140
give rise to self-expansion,
meaning to self-efficacy.

01:59:59.140 --> 02:00:02.970
So what this self-expansion
model is really about is

02:00:02.970 --> 02:00:06.150
how great other people that we
are close to and romantically

02:00:06.150 --> 02:00:09.470
attached to can potentially make us feel,

02:00:09.470 --> 02:00:12.730
in terms of what they say,
in terms of what they do,

02:00:12.730 --> 02:00:17.730
in terms of the way in which
we believe they feel about us.

02:00:18.170 --> 02:00:20.880
So it doesn't necessarily
have to involve explicit

02:00:20.880 --> 02:00:24.070
statements of them telling
us how great we are,

02:00:24.070 --> 02:00:27.100
or them doing great gestures for us,

02:00:27.100 --> 02:00:30.280
but how we actually
feel they feel about us.

02:00:30.280 --> 02:00:32.780
Turns out to be a very
strong parameter in terms

02:00:32.780 --> 02:00:36.250
of how we feel about ourselves
and the relationship overall.

02:00:36.250 --> 02:00:37.707
Now, some of you out there
are probably thinking,

02:00:37.707 --> 02:00:38.860
"Oh yeah, isn't there this thing

02:00:38.860 --> 02:00:40.850
of the love languages?" Right?

02:00:40.850 --> 02:00:42.880
I don't have any neuroscience
to support, I think,

02:00:42.880 --> 02:00:44.777
the love languages, I'm not
super familiar with this,

02:00:44.777 --> 02:00:48.020
and I didn't list it out,
but that some people are...

02:00:49.320 --> 02:00:52.090
Their autonomic nervous
system, if you will,

02:00:52.090 --> 02:00:56.470
tends to be very responsive
to gifts, or to quality time,

02:00:56.470 --> 02:00:58.230
or to physical touch, or acts of kindness.

02:00:58.230 --> 02:00:59.310
I think I've got a few of these right.

02:00:59.310 --> 02:01:00.280
I probably have a few wrong.

02:01:00.280 --> 02:01:01.670
Anyway, they're easy to find online.

02:01:01.670 --> 02:01:05.420
And people do tend to have
a bias toward two or three

02:01:05.420 --> 02:01:06.760
of these things that are especially

02:01:06.760 --> 02:01:07.880
meaningful for them.

02:01:07.880 --> 02:01:10.380
And when I hear meaningful,
I hear they tend to push

02:01:10.380 --> 02:01:12.970
the autonomic nervous system
and neurochemical systems

02:01:12.970 --> 02:01:15.540
of the brain and body in a
direction that makes us feel good

02:01:15.540 --> 02:01:18.060
as opposed to lousy or neutral.

02:01:18.060 --> 02:01:22.300
In any event, this study
looked at whether or not

02:01:22.300 --> 02:01:26.410
people have high levels of self-expansion

02:01:26.410 --> 02:01:29.060
through the actions or statements

02:01:29.060 --> 02:01:32.275
of their significant other,
and how that influences

02:01:32.275 --> 02:01:36.250
their perception of people
outside the relationship.

02:01:36.250 --> 02:01:38.980
Meaning how attractive
they perceive people

02:01:38.980 --> 02:01:40.870
outside the relationship to be,

02:01:40.870 --> 02:01:43.280
turns out to be strongly influenced

02:01:43.280 --> 02:01:48.280
by, A, whether or not their
self-expansion is very strongly

02:01:50.270 --> 02:01:53.164
driven by the other person
that they are involved with,

02:01:53.164 --> 02:01:55.470
that they're in the
romantic relationship with,

02:01:55.470 --> 02:01:57.600
and whether or not that's
being expressed to them.

02:01:57.600 --> 02:01:59.391
So here's how the study went.

02:01:59.391 --> 02:02:03.910
First of all, they rated
or categorized individuals

02:02:03.910 --> 02:02:06.180
on the basis of the self-expansion metric.

02:02:06.180 --> 02:02:09.980
Some people have more of
a potential to experience

02:02:09.980 --> 02:02:11.830
self-expansion through others, right?

02:02:11.830 --> 02:02:15.070
Some of us feel great about
ourselves and we're topped off,

02:02:15.070 --> 02:02:17.880
the others don't feel so
great about themselves,

02:02:17.880 --> 02:02:20.380
but they can feel much
better in response to praise,

02:02:20.380 --> 02:02:23.840
in particular praise or
self-expansion type behaviors

02:02:23.840 --> 02:02:25.860
or statements from people
that we really care about.

02:02:25.860 --> 02:02:28.240
And still other people
are a mixture of the two.

02:02:28.240 --> 02:02:30.370
They moderate levels of both.

02:02:30.370 --> 02:02:32.010
So they rated them on this scale.

02:02:32.010 --> 02:02:33.440
And then they had people

02:02:33.440 --> 02:02:37.250
experience self-expansion narratives.

02:02:37.250 --> 02:02:39.810
They heard their significant
others say really terrific

02:02:39.810 --> 02:02:42.870
things about them and about the
relationship, in particular,

02:02:42.870 --> 02:02:46.060
that the relationship that
they have was exciting,

02:02:46.060 --> 02:02:47.370
novel and challenging.

02:02:47.370 --> 02:02:49.080
So that was one form of self-expansion.

02:02:49.080 --> 02:02:51.600
And they went into some detail
as to why that was the case

02:02:51.600 --> 02:02:52.977
in their particular relationship.

02:02:52.977 --> 02:02:57.910
Or they heard a narrative
from their significant other

02:02:57.910 --> 02:03:02.210
about strong feelings
of love between the two

02:03:02.210 --> 02:03:04.640
that had been experienced
previously in the relationship.

02:03:04.640 --> 02:03:07.670
So in the one case, it
directed more towards them.

02:03:07.670 --> 02:03:08.503
And in the other case,

02:03:08.503 --> 02:03:10.580
it's more about the relationship itself.

02:03:10.580 --> 02:03:14.470
And then they did brain
imaging of one person

02:03:14.470 --> 02:03:17.130
in the relationship while
that person assessed

02:03:17.130 --> 02:03:21.150
the attractiveness of people
outside the relationship.

02:03:21.150 --> 02:03:23.900
And what they found was
that people who were primed

02:03:23.900 --> 02:03:28.900
for this self-expansion had
lower activation of brain areas

02:03:29.470 --> 02:03:32.590
associated with assessing
others' attractiveness

02:03:32.590 --> 02:03:36.650
than did the people who experienced
a lot of self-expansion.

02:03:36.650 --> 02:03:40.010
Now the takeaway from that,
at least the way I read

02:03:40.010 --> 02:03:44.090
the study is if you're with
somebody who really benefits

02:03:44.090 --> 02:03:47.273
from or experiences a
lot of self-expansion,

02:03:48.720 --> 02:03:50.540
unless you really want
them to pay attention

02:03:50.540 --> 02:03:52.710
to the attractiveness of other people,

02:03:52.710 --> 02:03:56.380
it stands to reason
that they would benefit

02:03:56.380 --> 02:04:01.220
from more self-expansion type
gestures or statements, okay?

02:04:01.220 --> 02:04:02.724
Not so much centered on the relationship.

02:04:02.724 --> 02:04:04.610
We have such a great relationship.

02:04:04.610 --> 02:04:07.070
There's so much love,
it's so great, that too,

02:04:07.070 --> 02:04:09.700
but in the context of this
study and these findings,

02:04:09.700 --> 02:04:13.000
that the person is really
terrific, that the relationship

02:04:13.000 --> 02:04:14.970
that they've created
together is really exciting,

02:04:14.970 --> 02:04:17.970
novel, and challenging, that
there's a narrative around

02:04:17.970 --> 02:04:19.709
the relationship that
really has a lot to do

02:04:19.709 --> 02:04:23.020
with the dynamics between the
individuals, in particular,

02:04:23.020 --> 02:04:25.400
that the person who really
likes self-expansion

02:04:25.400 --> 02:04:27.210
is vital to that dynamic, okay?

02:04:27.210 --> 02:04:28.890
So it's not looking
down at the relationship

02:04:28.890 --> 02:04:30.140
as a set of equals.

02:04:30.140 --> 02:04:32.550
There is this bias
written into this of that

02:04:32.550 --> 02:04:35.030
this person is really
essential for the relationship.

02:04:35.030 --> 02:04:36.790
I'm not saying this is
something that anyone has to do.

02:04:36.790 --> 02:04:38.090
I'm not not saying this is right or wrong.

02:04:38.090 --> 02:04:40.160
This is just what the data say.

02:04:40.160 --> 02:04:43.140
But what's remarkable
is that in the absence

02:04:43.140 --> 02:04:47.140
of those statements, people who have,

02:04:47.140 --> 02:04:50.720
or that rate high on this
scale of self-expansion

02:04:50.720 --> 02:04:54.500
rate attractive alternative
partners as more attractive.

02:04:54.500 --> 02:04:58.070
Now, that's interesting to
me, because it may means that

02:04:58.070 --> 02:05:00.890
their actual perception
of others is changing.

02:05:00.890 --> 02:05:02.252
It's not that their opportunity

02:05:02.252 --> 02:05:04.940
to see others is changing, right?

02:05:04.940 --> 02:05:08.440
This is not a matter of
them somehow getting access

02:05:08.440 --> 02:05:11.180
or no access to attractive
alternative partners.

02:05:11.180 --> 02:05:12.560
Again, attractive alternative partners,

02:05:12.560 --> 02:05:14.980
literally the language in
the title of this paper,

02:05:14.980 --> 02:05:17.180
they're still seeing all
these attractive people.

02:05:17.180 --> 02:05:21.490
It's just that if they're
feeling filled up, in air quotes,

02:05:21.490 --> 02:05:24.647
psychologically filled
up, emotionally filled up,

02:05:24.647 --> 02:05:28.460
autonomically filled,
enhanced in the language

02:05:28.460 --> 02:05:31.520
that we're using today by
the self-expansion narrative,

02:05:31.520 --> 02:05:35.320
well then the same set of
attractive faces appear

02:05:35.320 --> 02:05:38.510
less attractive to a given individual.

02:05:38.510 --> 02:05:40.944
Now, whether or not this
predicts cheating or loyalty,

02:05:40.944 --> 02:05:43.020
[laughs] I certainly can't say.

02:05:43.020 --> 02:05:45.800
That would be very hard
to assess in neuroimaging.

02:05:45.800 --> 02:05:50.800
And there, of course,
people rarely if ever

02:05:50.820 --> 02:05:53.240
report accurately their cheating behavior.

02:05:53.240 --> 02:05:56.240
There's some studies in which
confidentiality is assured

02:05:56.240 --> 02:05:59.200
to the point where people
seem to be more trusting

02:05:59.200 --> 02:06:01.830
and willing to reveal cheating behavior.

02:06:01.830 --> 02:06:03.620
But if you look at the
statistics on cheating behavior,

02:06:03.620 --> 02:06:07.130
it's very hard to track
because people lie all the time

02:06:07.130 --> 02:06:09.250
about their cheating in
and outside of the context

02:06:09.250 --> 02:06:12.600
of psychological and neuroimaging studies.

02:06:12.600 --> 02:06:15.267
But I find this study, again, the title,

02:06:15.267 --> 02:06:17.680
"Manipulation of
Self-expansion Alters Responses

02:06:17.680 --> 02:06:19.180
to Attractive Alternative Partners"

02:06:19.180 --> 02:06:22.540
to be absolutely fascinating,
because again, it points

02:06:22.540 --> 02:06:26.830
to the fact that the
interactions with our significant

02:06:26.830 --> 02:06:30.480
others shapes our autonomic
arousal, shapes our perception

02:06:30.480 --> 02:06:35.250
of self and thereby shapes our
perception of other potential

02:06:35.250 --> 02:06:36.780
partners in the outside world,

02:06:36.780 --> 02:06:40.140
or shuts us down to the
potential of other people

02:06:40.140 --> 02:06:41.500
in the outside world.

02:06:41.500 --> 02:06:43.040
So when I hear statements such as,

02:06:43.040 --> 02:06:44.660
it's important that you love yourself

02:06:44.660 --> 02:06:47.220
in order to really fall in
love with somebody else,

02:06:47.220 --> 02:06:51.330
or it is when one is not
looking for a relationship

02:06:51.330 --> 02:06:52.710
that they're most likely to fall in love

02:06:52.710 --> 02:06:54.303
and form a stable relationship,

02:06:56.290 --> 02:06:58.970
I can filter that through
these findings to say that

02:06:59.970 --> 02:07:04.203
it's really the person who
needs a lot of self-expansion,

02:07:05.230 --> 02:07:09.140
stimulating statements or
actions coming from other people

02:07:09.140 --> 02:07:13.790
that is most prone to seeing
other potential partners

02:07:13.790 --> 02:07:15.750
out in the world as attractive.

02:07:15.750 --> 02:07:17.610
And in this sense,

02:07:17.610 --> 02:07:19.690
we can return to the
autonomic nervous system

02:07:19.690 --> 02:07:23.430
as a glass that it can be filled up

02:07:23.430 --> 02:07:24.520
through various contexts.

02:07:24.520 --> 02:07:27.280
It can be filled up through
our own ability to regulate it.

02:07:27.280 --> 02:07:30.640
It can be filled up through
other people's ability

02:07:30.640 --> 02:07:32.840
to enhance our sense of wellbeing.

02:07:32.840 --> 02:07:37.090
And in some sense, this points
to an idea where it is true

02:07:37.090 --> 02:07:39.070
that the better that we
can feel about ourselves

02:07:39.070 --> 02:07:43.560
in the absence of any
self-expansion type input

02:07:43.560 --> 02:07:45.670
from somebody else really does place us

02:07:45.670 --> 02:07:48.170
on more stable grounds,
such that when we do receive

02:07:48.170 --> 02:07:50.530
that praise, or we do receive
those acts of kindness,

02:07:50.530 --> 02:07:53.280
or service, or physical
touch or whatever they are,

02:07:53.280 --> 02:07:58.280
that we are able to further
enhance the way that we feel,

02:07:58.750 --> 02:08:02.170
but that we don't necessarily
tether all of our feelings

02:08:02.170 --> 02:08:06.680
of self-worth or self-expansion
to that one individual.

02:08:06.680 --> 02:08:10.250
So you might think that if
person A can only receive

02:08:10.250 --> 02:08:14.510
the self-expansion from the
statements, from the action

02:08:14.510 --> 02:08:16.750
of the they're involved with, person B,

02:08:16.750 --> 02:08:19.640
that that will form a very stable bond,

02:08:19.640 --> 02:08:21.400
but what this study
points to is the fact that

02:08:21.400 --> 02:08:23.520
that's a very unstable bond.

02:08:23.520 --> 02:08:26.190
That person A is actually very susceptible

02:08:26.190 --> 02:08:27.480
to the attractiveness of others,

02:08:27.480 --> 02:08:30.340
because they're so desperately
attached to this notion

02:08:30.340 --> 02:08:32.580
of self-expansion, even
if they don't realize it.

02:08:32.580 --> 02:08:35.320
And so this really does
point to the idea that,

02:08:35.320 --> 02:08:38.920
well, it is important to link
our autonomic nervous systems

02:08:38.920 --> 02:08:42.370
to establish desire, love, and attachment

02:08:42.370 --> 02:08:45.910
that we want to have a stable
internal representation

02:08:45.910 --> 02:08:49.160
of ourselves, a stable
autonomic nervous system

02:08:49.160 --> 02:08:53.330
to some degree in other so
that we can be in stable

02:08:53.330 --> 02:08:55.720
romantic partnership
with another individual,

02:08:55.720 --> 02:08:57.410
if that what we're really trying to do.

02:08:57.410 --> 02:08:58.822
So until now, I've been
weaving together studies

02:08:58.822 --> 02:09:01.990
from the field of experimental psychology

